I think everything that has culminated in the Jurassic film series since the early 90s has really left an impression for the past and present generation.

Four years have passed since Isla Nublar faced a violent volcanic eruption along with the Lockwood Manor incident, so Owen, Claire, and adoptive daughter Maisie have moved on to accept our modern day lives are now shared with living, breathing dinosaurs. Many familiar, but also uncovering new, dangerous species never seen before. However, Earth's ecosystem and balance are greatly affected by their presence that it also brought the attention of doctors Alan Grant, Ellie Sattler, and Ian Malcolm to step forward, join forces with Owen and his group, and stop these new threats.

While I was overly excited to see Sam Neill, Laura Dern, and Jeff Goldblum reunited since the first Jurassic Park movie, I was really hoping there was going to be a solid story to conclude the Jurassic World trilogy. Unfortunately, the story was so-so to me and that's about it. Although it improves over its slow-paced predecessor Fallen Kingdom, director Colin Trevorrow's follow-up Dominion falls short as a whole. He succeeded in 2015 with Jurassic World, but I was expecting more could be addressed on what throws these characters into conflict. Using genetically-altered locusts and velociraptor Blue's offspring Beta as plot devices sounds interesting, but feels kind of lacking in execution.

This film will never reach landmark status as the 1993 original that will forever remain timeless, but Dominion is a movie that gives a tribute of sorts to what has transpired in the years that followed. Though I wouldn't call this movie awful, it gives off a feeble conclusion to the Jurassic World film trilogy.

"Roara" the T-Rex and Her Human Play Toys
michaelxqh12 June 2022
Warning: Spoilers
2 out of 3 found this helpful. Was this review helpful? Sign in to vote.
Permalink
Conclusion the Jurassic series is no doubt the hardest to make: too many relationships to be completed, too many mysteries to be resolved, too many philosophies to be conveyed... After 3 decades and 6 movies, the riveting story between humans and dinosaurs ends in the not-so-exciting roar of the iconic tyrannosaurus rex - I'm naming her "Roara" by the way.

One big problem is the characters, who are just "dead". I feel no affection towards the old trio - Ellie's nonstop nosiness, Alan's love-driven motivation, and Gold... sorry, Ian's quirky humor, not a fan of any of those. In fact, their appearance serves only for the family reunion of the final act, a device that doesn't incite my nostalgia for the original Jurassic Park, but is quite awkward to watch. Owen and Claire continue their dalliance and misplaced sense of parenthood, which isn't explained anyhow. Maisie, good god girl, what exactly do you want? Her rebellious behavior got her abducted which she didn't even try to escape, and when she realized her true identity, instead of maturation, she ran away - where's the logistic? Lewis, who looks like Tim Cook and acts like a peanut-eating wealthy psychopath businessman, stomps around and slams his chair when provoked - why would such an emotionless villain suddenly have tantrum? Not to mention there're Ramsay and Kayla, who are purely tool characters without personal will. All of these figures play their part just according to the script, guiding the audience like a group of programmed NPCs.

However, I have to compliment the Second Act, which is surfeited with action scenes. Objectives are clear, stunts are breathtaking, creativity is shown. Environmental layouts are vast while meticulous, comprising exotic market, humid jungle, frozen lake, and lightless cave - all are fantastic stages for various creatures and actions. Most of the dinosaurs that the I envisioned participate - except for Blue and the mosasaurus - providing different levels of tension. Making the idiotic antagonist die to the dilophosauruses was a great allusion. I personally enjoyed the weaponization of the raptors, very inventive and definitely a human thing to do.

Let's talk about ideas as the film brings up three. One, purpose and potential of genetically replicated beings, in which Maisie realizes that she is allowed to be unique - an idea mentioned by countless books and movies, and is restated again. Also, the cloning technique further cures the swarm crisis, which leads us to the second idea: monopolization of food resources by putting dinosaur genomes in locusts. This one is not only unethical, illegal, but also stupid: there are so many ways in which dinosaurs could be used to make money, yet Biosyn chooses the most irrelevant and uncontrollable approach. Despite that, what nonsense script writer came up with the proposal that insects could be a great "final boss" for a dinosaur-themed movie? Jurassic World: Dominion of Bugs? Third, symbiosis of humans and dinosaurs, which is only brought up in the first and last 5 minutes of the film. Ironically, the entire plot happens in a society where both organisms co-exist, and the world hasn't really changed anyway through the adventures that occurred. In short, this piece of work presents zero nutritious moral to reflect on.

Moreover, if we examine what the protagonists actually accomplished, it's not hard to tell that they are the destructive ones. Ellie and Alan transgresses company policies just for a conspiracy article, disturbing the harmony of mutant locusts which cause wildfire and mortalities. Owen and Kayla are warned not to land twice before crushing, damaging public infrastructures. Maisie recklessly releases a predatory animal, indirectly killing innocent office workers. Finally, the group shut down the premises' power without permission, and could be charged deliberate vandalism and murder of Lewis.

That's about it for the last Jurassic World: great actions sequences, but below standard everywhere else.

3/10

I saw this with my nephew yesterday. The CGI, sound design, and camera were all topnotch as you would expect from a Jurassic Park film. Even the few shots of practical effects were quality. This was very expensive to make for sure.

But everything else was flat and mindlessly, needlessly complicated. The first big problem I had with it was that it's WAY too long by at least an hour. The runtime became almost torture. It's like they kept inventing problems for the characters to solve for the sake of a longer duration.

The next thing was that there was too much going on. There were multiple plots within the plot so it felt disjointed. And some of them were pointless. You've got a human clone with a story about her mother and the clone's search for her identity, a locust plague, a conspiracy, some more stuff, and then the dinosaurs. It was cluttered.

With any Jurassic Park movie, I think less is more. The original adaptation did it best and I don't believe its magic will ever be recreated: A mysterious park with cloned dinosaurs who escape. The characters then try to survive the chaos. Throw in unbelievable filmmaking craftsmanship with lovable characters and we had a winner. That's it. That's all we needed.

I will say that it was better than Fallen Kingdom. I can't declare that I outright hated Dominion but I wouldn't bother with it again and found it forgettable. Having the original cast back was nice to see but it didn't do anything to help beyond the warm nostalgic factor.

This certainly wasn't a fitting end to the franchise.

Dinosaurs are just a normal part of modern life on Earth now but locusts are now the main problem everyone's worried about? Right, whatever!

The Allosaurus stalking the entire character cast around the jeep and making no attempt to attack anyone until the plot decides its convenient. A Pteradactyl that can rip apart a plane like it's a feather pillow, stick its beak straight into one of the jet engines and sustain no injury whatsoever, Owen Grady and a couple others chasing Parasaurs on horseback and trying to lasso one of them like it's some country western... These are just some of the cheesy, overblown and poorly written aspects of Dominion... goshamorrell11 June 2022
Twenty-nine years ago, when "Jurassic Park" was released, computer-generated and digitally composited effects were still relatively new, but director Steven Spielberg's team raised them to a new level of credibility by deploying them sparingly, often in nighttime and rainy scenes, and mixing them with old-fashioned practical FX work (mainly puppets and large-scale models). The result conjured primal wonder and terror in the minds of viewers. The T-Rex attack in particular was so brilliantly constructed and unrelentingly frightening that it put this writer sideways in his seat, one arm raised in front of his face as if to defend against a dinosaur attack. When there was a break in the mayhem, Spielberg cut to a very quiet scene, letting everyone hear how many people in the audience had been screaming in fright, which of course led to raucous laughter and a release of tension (a foolproof showman's trick). A small girl sitting near this writer regarded his still-terror-contorted body and asked, "Mister, are you all right?"There's nothing in "Jurassic World: Dominion" that comes close to that first "Jurassic Park" T-Rex attack, or any other scene in it. Or for that matter, any of the scenes in the Spielberg-directed sequel "The Lost World," which made the best of an inevitable cash-grab scenario by treating the film as an excuse to stage a series of dazzling large-scale action sequences, and giving Jeff Goldblum's chaos theorist Dr. Ian Malcolm the action hero job. Goldblum, who reprises his role in "Dominion" alongside fellow original cast members Sam Neill and Laura Dern, turned his "Lost World" performance into a wry-yet-cranky meta-commentary on corporate capitalism. For that matter, there's nothing in this new film as good as the best parts of "Jurassic Park III," "Jurassic World," and "Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom," the latter which suffered from diminishing-returns syndrome, yet still managed to stage a crackerjack action scene or dino attack here and there. J. A. Bayona's mixed-bag "Fallen Kingdom," which provides literal as well as figurative DNA to the plot of "Dominion," had the most surprising pivots since the original, conjuring Spielbergian images of wonder (think of that mournful shot of the brachiosaur left behind on the dock) and mixing gothic horror and haunted house-movie elements into its second half. "Jurassic Park" creator Michael Crichton's original inspiration, Mary Shelley's Frankenstein, was referenced through the character of Maisie Lockwood (Isabella Sermon), a clone created by John Hammond's business partner to replace the daughter that he lost.

jdesando10 June 2022
"We're racing toward the extinction of our species. We not only lack dominion over nature, we're subordinate to it." Ian Malcolm (Jeff Goldblum)

Jurassic World Dominion may arguably be almost as good as the original. Anyway, it's quite entertaining summer adventure fare with the CGI dinosaurs more realistic than ever, including the biggest carnivore in the world, yes more fearsome than T Rex. The real dinosaurs are the returning veterans Laura Dern, Bryce Dallas Howard, Sam Neill, and the inimitable Jeff Goldblum. You just can't put them down even with the failure of at least two other theme parks.

In order to fulfill the rigid requirements of the adventure genre, there must be a serious bad guy, and this Jurassic has Lewis Dodgson (Campbell Scott). He runs a sanctuary lab that houses homeless dinos but really serves as a platform for world dominion.

You got it-the four heroes go through innumerable dino encounters to stop the maniac genius. But enough plot, of which there is nary a nuance, because the relationships of good people throughout are pleasantly emphasized so that we care about each one.

We saw this Jurassic in a Phoenix Theater's Dolby Atmos, a splendid screening venue that titillates with sound moving your seat ever so slightly. When the dino stomps, our seats respond with a tingle. So, our Jurassic joy is watching and feeling the best motion pictures have to offer. Together with the most comfortable seats in town, it's a pleasant safari with monstrous animals, some over 60 million years old.

The larger point writer/director Colin Trevorrow and writer Emily Carmichael make is about cooperation-be it among family and co-workers or dinos and humans, we have no choice but to work in harmony. Or otherwise, damnation it is or total annihilation. Having lived in the last three years with a microscopic monster, it's nice to see ones big as buildings with the hope that we will survive together, if only in the salutary world of Hollywood dreams.

Jurassic World Dominion is a most pleasant way to enjoy a summer night out, even when it hints of extinction:

"The doomsday clock might be out of time." Ian Malcolm.

both gangs team up
ferguson-68 June 2022
Greetings again from the darkness. It's been almost 30 years since Steve Spielberg captivated us, and John Hammond (the late Sir Richard Attenborough) "spared no expense" in stunning Dr. Alan Grant (Sam Neill) with our first look at dinosaurs in JURASSIC PARK (1993). Best-selling author Michael Crichton's original characters and ideas have since spun off into THE LOST WORLD: JURASSIC PARK (1997), JURASSIC PARK III (2001), JURASSIC WORLD (2015), and JURASSIC WORLD: FALLEN KINGDOM (2018). We now have this latest franchise entry to cap off the second dinosaur trilogy, and it finds director Colin Trevorrow back at the helm. He also wrote the story and screenplay with Derek Connolly and Emily Carmichael.

The big news here (other than the dinosaurs) is the 4-doctor reunion of Dr. Alan Grant (Neill), Dr. Ellie Sattler (Laura Dern), Dr. Ian Malcolm (Jeff Goldblum), and Dr. Henry Wu (BD Wong). It's the first time all of these characters have reunited since the original, and those of us who hold a special place in our movie heart for the transformative 1993 film, are most appreciative of the nostalgic touch. However, the hopes for a magical finale to conclude the franchise are dashed in the film's opening segment ... a cringe-worthy "news" report designed to catch us up four years after the destruction of Isla Numbar, and set the stage for what's to come.

You might assume that dinosaurs roaming our planet would be the headliner, but somehow locusts get the nod. Well, they are genetically modified locusts threatening the world's non-Biosyn food supply. See, Biosyn is the evil corporation run by twitchy CEO Lewis Dodgson (Campbell Scott) that is attempting to control dinosaurs, the food supply, and even human cloning via DNA manipulation. It's that last part that brings Maisie Lockwood (an excellent Isabella Sermon) into the fold, and the DNA-mix also provides an easy punchline to Trevorrow's approach to this final film (blending DNA from the two trilogies). Maisie has been living deep in the Sierra Nevada forest with Owen Grady (Chris Pratt) and Claire Dearing (Bryce Dallas Howard). When poachers nab both the offspring of Owen's favorite raptor and his quasi-offspring Maisie, the hunt is on. The only question remaining is how are they going to finesse this so that the old crew (Grant and Ellie) collides with the new crew (Owen and Claire)?

A stop in Malta to confront smuggler Santos (an impeccably dressed Dichen Lachman) results in the film's most frenetic action sequence. As Owen eludes trained killer-raptors while zipping his motorcycle across streets, alleys, and stairwells, Claire is sprinting (not in high heels) across rooftops like she's Jason Bourne or James Bond. While Owen and Claire deliver the heart-pounding action, Ellie has tracked down Grant on a dig in New Mexico, where he's "educating" a group of teenagers who remain glued to their mobile devices. Ellie convinces Grant to help in her mission to expose Biosyn, but we get the feeling he's making the trip for her, not to save humanity. With an assist from ice-cold pilot-for-hire Kayla Watts (DeWanda Wise), everyone ends in Italy's Dolomite Mountains at Biosyn's stunning headquarters. Slowly the connections become apparent, as it's Malcolm (Goldblum) who is the resident philosopher (all evil corps need one), and the one who has been feeding intel to Ellie.

The rest of the movie exists so that all of these characters, along with Biosyn whistleblower Ramsay (Mamoudou Athie) can get in and out of trouble and dodge various stages of peril. The callbacks and nods to previous 'Jurassic' films are numerous. Some work and some don't. Malcolm's sardonic quips are mostly in tune, Grant's grumping and knowledge are spot on, and Ellie has remarkably little to do for someone who is responsible for one of the two main plot lines. Owen and Claire spend the bulk of their non-Malta time consistently recreating the facial expressions that have become all too familiar, though of course, Owen does get to hold out his palm in an attempt at controlling dinosaurs. There is a well-timed small dose of John Williams' iconic score from 1993, but it's the musical work of composer Michael Giacchino who mostly guides us along the way.

Credit goes to director Trevorrow for the multiple location shoots around the globe, which helps minimize the set pieces ... most of which disappoint. Especially surprising was the weak CGI effort in the mines as some of the characters end up where they shouldn't be. DNA manipulation run amok is perhaps the underlying theme, but we have to ask why this is ... all we really desire are cool dinosaurs and a story that makes sense. Despite the film's best shot coming at the end - a Mosasaurus underwater - we do hope that, in regards to continuing the franchise, Hollywood doesn't find a way.

Opens in theaters on June 10, 2022.

A satisfactory conclusion to both the "Park" and "World" stories that should hold fans over until the inevitable future installments
MrDHWong9 June 2022
"Jurassic World: Dominion" is the third "Jurassic World" film and the sixth film in the "Jurassic Park" series. Directed and co-written by Colin Trevorrow ("Safety Not Guaranteed", "The Book of Henry"), it is a satisfactory conclusion to both the "Park" and "World" stories that should hold fans over until the inevitable future installments.

Four years after the events of "Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom", Isla Nublar has been destroyed by a volcano and dinosaurs have now escaped into the real world. As a result, the future of the planet is in doubt since these once extinct creatures are reclaiming the Earth, making life increasingly difficult for all the other human beings and animals who are forced to co-exist alongside them. In an effort to curb this problem, a secret experiment involving more genetic engineering is underway in a secluded location, which, if successful, will allow humanity to regain its place at the top of the food chain and keep these ancient beasts under control.

Since the release of the first film back in 1993, the "Jurassic Park/World" series has had an interesting run among filmgoers. The original featured groundbreaking special effects, a great cast of memorable characters, and that iconic John Williams musical score to help cement it as one of the most iconic films of the 90s. On the other hand, all of the sequels have yielded less favourable results in terms of entertainment value, ranging from decent popcorn flicks to downright insulting to longtime fans. It seems the one that started it all has simply set the bar so high that everything else following it looks so poor in comparison. After almost three decades, the story that began so long ago finally draws to a close here in "Jurassic World Dominion", which ends things on a fairly acceptable note.

I've never been one to take the "Jurassic Park/World" films too seriously considering their entire premise is pretty farfetched. I mean, how seriously can you really take the concept of bringing dinosaurs back to life using mosquito blood and frog DNA? But despite that, I still find them highly entertaining for what they are, and that is watching dinosaurs wreaking havoc and exposing the hubris of humanity. I still remember being wowed by the original film as a kid and rewatching it as an adult made me realise how well it holds up today. "Jurassic World Dominion", which is intended to be the final film in the franchise to focus around the initial story set up in 1993, features all of this and then some, so if that's what you're craving, the film delivers just that.

For the most part, this film's effects look pretty good but still not as good as how they did back in the 1993 film. This is because that one used animatronics for whenever the filmmakers showed the dinosaurs up close and CGI only for when they were seen at a distance. However, since the first "Jurassic World" film back in 2015, the animatronics appear to have been completely discarded in favour of entirely CGI dinosaurs, which I have mixed feelings about. Sure, some of the computer-generated dinosaurs seem naturally integrated into a shot but others look so obviously added in during post-production that they stick out like a sore thumb. I understand that it's cheaper to use CGI nowadays but if these modern filmmakers truly wanted to leave an impression on viewers, then they should have at least used some animatronics wherever possible.

One major problem I had with this film was its bloated second act. Without giving away spoilers, all I will say is that there are three different stories going on at once, each with a different emotional feeling. For example, one moment we might see characters being chased by dinosaurs through a busy city street and then immediately after we'll see a slow paced scene of expository dialogue that feels shoehorned in there for storytelling purposes. These parts would have worked out better if they each had some kind of overarching link to one another but instead these weird shifts in tone causes the film drag at the most inopportune times. This is where I started to lose interest in the human side of the story and wished everyone would just meet up with one another already just to get things over with.

I do think the film made good use of the idea of humans and dinosaurs being made to co-exist with one another. Some people are shown trying to rescue the dinosaurs to take care of them while others trade them on the black market as exotic pets. There are also a number of brief but well-shot scenes of a group of triceratops and elephants walking side-by-side along the African Serengeti as well as some large pterosaurs patrolling the skies of New York City, with some even settling nests on the tops of skyscrapers. I guess I just like seeing such a jarring juxtaposition of the old and new inhabitants of the world being forced to live in the same eco-system, but at the same time being reminded that this is not the natural order of things. It's like what Dr. John Hammond (Richard Attenborough) said at the end of "The Lost World: Jurassic Park" in that "...these creatures require our absence to survive, not our help".

As a pair, both Chris Pratt and Bryce Dallas Howard were fun dual protagonists as Owen and Claire, but they are rarely shown doing anything solo in this film. Though I liked that the two were a loving couple at first, I would have preferred if we could have seen them do things on their own to allow for their characters to develop individually, instead of being two inseparable halves throughout most of the film. Additionally, the young Isabella Sermon felt like she was going to waste as Maisie Lockwood, the pair's adoptive daughter. Maisie never felt like an actual fleshed-out character but rather a plot device used to advance the film forward until the climax. It's a shame because I saw potential in her back in the conclusion of "Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom", but I suppose that was never meant to be.

It was also nice to see the original trio of Sam Neill, Laura Dern, and Jeff Goldblum return after almost 30 years as Dr. Alan Grant, Dr. Ellie Sattler, and Dr. Ian Malcolm, respectively. Though their reunion here is based entirely on nostalgia, their presence at least helped elevate the film above what could have been a forgettable conclusion to this long-running series. Again, like with the dinosaurs and humans, I liked the juxtaposition of the three characters from the "Park" films with the new "World" ones of Owen and Claire. There was something satisfying about watching the five of them work together to outsmart the dinosaurs with their different levels of general knowledge in their respective fields, whether it be Dr. Grant's palaeontology or Owen's ability to communicate with Velociraptors.

Although it's clear by now the series has run its course, I will admit that for all intents and purposes, I've enjoyed watching all six of these "Jurassic" films for the popcorn entertainment they are. Through the good and bad, I have nonetheless loved seeing how the filmmakers made dinosaurs live again and had them roar their deafening roars. But if you ask me, the series needs to go on a lengthy hiatus before we ever see these cretaceous creatures on the big screen again. Though knowing what a cash cow the franchise has become (like a certain sci-fi series set in a galaxy far, far away), it's only a matter of time before Universal Studios decides to milk it even further with spin-offs, prequels, video games, etc. Until then, let's just appreciate what we've got for now.

I rate it 6.5/10.

This review will likely be drowned by an influx of uncritical "I liked it" reviews. I don't really care. I feel like I ought to put my thoughts out here.

I'd say if you really want to, go see it and form your own opinion. I don't really care either way.

As a film Jurassic World Dominion is at least competently shot and coherent throughout unlike its predecessor Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom. However... As far as writing, pacing, and characters go, it's not particularly great. A large portion of the film could be better allocated. Entire scenes could either be reworked or all-out removed. The two main plotlines barely connect (and the Locusts one could be scrapped altogether) and the inclusion of the original film's cast felt like pandering and nostalgia bait (something highlighted by the inexplicable fanservice that is the romance between Sattler and Grant).

The animals.

Some creatures barely matter, such as Moros and Dimetrodon, and those who do matter are often shafted in favour of new creatures which show up, do a thing, and then never come back again. Scenes like those involving the Pyroraptor could be reworked to make the animal more important instead of leaving it as yet another dromaeosaur to throw onto the 'Jurassic' pile. Beta, Blue's parthenogenic baby, is forgotten about for most of the film until at some point she becomes relevant again.

The characters.

I've already mentioned the main thing of what I disliked about Sattler/Grant, but there's also the fact that Grant as a character feels limp. He's a very passive character. Things just sort of happen to him instead of them happening from his own initiative like in the original JP. Maisie's personal arc is resolved, so that's nice, but her being a clone only ever comes up in relevance to that. By the end of the film it's likely that she will STILL have to stay in hiding, that was never closed off or anything like that. The original cast being present was also limp. They were functionally interchangeable with other, non-returning characters, which is not what you want your legacy cast to feel like especially not in a film like this.

Pacing.

Pacing is mentioned in my other paragraphs, but to get more into it: by removing or reallocating scenes you could get rid of the very "go to the place, do the thing" nature of this film. Things happen and people go to places but it never feels like these places are actually important. They could be interchanged with any other and I don't believe specific locales really mattered.

The thing this film has going for it is that it is, in fact, NOT Fallen Kingdom. FK was a worse film because it tried to be multiple films at once. This one almost over-corrected. It really goes without saying that while this isn't *the worst* Jurassic sequel, it most certainly isn't the best either. I won't even get into why I think Universal is quite a scummy company, cos I'll be here all night. Please be critical of the films you see and analyse them. You might even find things you'd never seen before.

Movie Studio creates dinosaur franchise. Move studio destroys dinosaur franchise

The change to portraying the dinosaurs as monsters rather than animals is the biggest transgression of the sequels as it fundamentally changes the audience's point of view. In JP1 & 2 you're not privy to anything the characters aren't; you're going through the experience WITH them. That's a deliberate, important creative decision by Spielberg. From JP3 onwards you're on the side of the "puppeteers", to use a timely comparison. You're now (as a viewer) more omniscient, instead of sympathetic, it's criminal really

Additionally, Dominion was never going to be dinosaurs battling humans in New York City. It was something that, would honour Crichton's work a little bit more. I don't think he ever wrote a fantasy book.

I think the he challenge for Trevorrow was getting to a place where the dinosaurs will be in this somewhat confined space, and obviously, still making sure all hell broke loose.

For me, it's the second half of the movie when they started to converge in that environment. It may have been just because I did grow up on "Jurassic Park," but each of these films rely on the humans not being able to just call an Uber and get out of there.

They have to be trapped in a confined space in order for the kind of sequences that these movies thrive on to exist. I also felt like we've been taken the on a journey that has a lot of new stuff in it in the first half. It's a lot of new ideas and new sequences. I felt, as we got toward the end of this meal that we'd been served, it was important to bring out some comfort dishes, and make sure that, as the characters collided with the "Jurassic Park" characters, it really felt like "Jurassic Park."

🚨Genuine Review From A Long Time Fan🚨
zendoss10 June 2022
I am just going to start this review off by stating this film is getting beyond too much hate. In fact a huge amount of the critiques are unfounded, inaccurate or hyprocritical. Is it a masterpiece? No. Is it great? Maybe not. Is it bad or terrible, or as offensive as these 1/10 reviews would have you believe? No. It's good. Sure it has flaws, it definitely ain't perfect.

However from a die hard super fan, who's seen all the films countless times, and the original Jurassic Park being my all time favourite, what I can say is that it was not anywhere close to what the critics or reviews would have you believe.

Before I get into the rest, let me state this. The Rise of Skywalker has lines like "They fly now!" and somehow Palpatine has returned! IMDb rating? 6.5/10. Furious 7 has Dwayne Johnson rip a minigun off a drone and use it manually after driving a ambulance off a bridge to crash it. Paul Walker also drives a car through three sky scrapers. IMDB rating? 7.3/10. Black Panther, Shang Chi and numerous other MCU films have legit PS2 level CGI...did anyone see the opening sequence to Doctor Strange 2? Yep, 7.3/10, 7.4/10 & 7.3/10 respectively for those films.

This film is currently sitting at 6/10 with only 10k votes, and IMDb tends to see things only drop. So my point is, does this film deserve all this hate, especially when you compare it to other films rated here? Well, no, it quite frankly is just unfair how many vague, brainless and cynical 1/10, 2/10 and 3/10 reviews are here. You don't have to like the film, but review fairly. This film, is at worst, mediocre. But I believe it's far more than that, both as a JP fan but also just as a crafted film.

No Way Home, let's use that for comparison. Decent acting? Check. A long run time, fairly messy, yet fun script and story? Check. Some humor? Check. References and callbacks? Check. Return of some iconic characters, fan service and world building? Check. A decent score that probably uses a lot of old tracks from prior films? Check. Good cinematography? Check. Good CGI and practical effects?

No, I'd say NWH is lacking there. And you know what? Dominion is near identical in every single category! Yet...NWH has 8.3/10 and Dominion has 6/10. You see the pattern here? This film is copping ridiculous amounts of hate. You don't have to be an award winning classic, an indie film or a Comic Book movie to be good.

Jurassic World Dominion is completely faithful and respectful to the legacy of all the films, the franchise itself and Michael Critchon's work.

It has beautiful cinematography, amazing CGI and awesome use of practical effects. It builds on the world and lore, and Giacchion's score is awesome as always. Grant feels like Grant. Ellie feels like Ellie. Malcolm feels like Malcolm. Owen and Claire are better than they've been, and Maisie (clone girl) is handled really well. The discourse around human cloning and the locust are straight out of Michael Critchon's work - Timeline, Micro, Westworld, Jurassic Park. Man playing god, manipulating nature and corporate greed.

Dominion puts the dinosaurs back a seat and focuses on the humans - yet people complain? Everyone praises the minimal use of the dinosaurs in the original, and states it's about man's misuse of technology and character arcs, whether it be Alan or Hammond. This film does the same. Heck they even got Dogdson back, just like the novels!

Does this film feature some wonky dialogue, some cheesy moments and plot conveniance? Sure. But it's not pure garbage.

It's staggering how many people use the word "dumb". Yet...where is this film dumb? Like where, seriously? I LOVE the other films, but they for sure have dumb moments or moments where logic gone. But this film surprisingly doesn't! Every decision, whether it be by Owen, or Claire or Grant or whoever, is the logical choice. There's not even any suspend your belief stunts or plot armor. The characters just genuinely navigate the locations well. No dumb dino prices, no militarised hybrids, no stupid decisions leading to chaos.

Heck people said they want less trained raptors and Blue, less "Fast & Furious over the top action", less Rexy saving the day, and more human content/character work.

Well guess what? They gave us that. It's funny we have people saying too much dinosaurs then people saying not enough dinosaurs.

What happened to being able to enjoy a summer block buster? This film is fun, enjoyable, nostalgic and true to it's roots. Half the negative reviews here don't even state any examples or evidence, they're just the typical "Hollywood bad" or "sequel bad". Don't get me wrong, I've hated plenty of films, but this film surely isn't any bit close to the current rating.

My only real major gripes is despite the long run time and a huge cast, there weren't enough casualties (even for side characters) and that the prologue should've been kept to open the film.

So in conclusion, please rate fairly, please don't be discouraged by reviews, and please form your own opinion. Love it? Great! Meh? Great! Hate it? Great! But don't just jump on the band wagon and don't straight up lie or pretend there's issues without evidence.

My final score is, as a fan 9/10, as a film 7.5/10.

Dinosaurs partly live alongside humans around the world, but an extinct giant swarm of locust mysteriously re-emerge threatening the worlds food supply and ecological system. After a kidnapping two groups cross paths while trying to put things right.

Director Colin Trevorrow offers a visually slick outing and even with its lengthy run time moves it along at a fast pace with some impressive staging.

The ensemble cast are great, even if the script is more focused on the espionage-like sets up. It includes Jurassic World favourites Chris Pratt, Bryce Dallas Howard and Isabella Sermon along with Jurassic Park's Sam Neill, Laura Dern and Jeff Goldblum. BD Wong also returns bridging the to trilogies as well as a few familiar faces from Fallen Kingdom and World. DeWanda Wise is particularly notable even if the character feels more from a James Bond or a Mission Impossible film.

It should be said that's it's great to see Dern, Goldblum and Neill reprise their roles appearing together for the first time since the 1993 film. However, Emily Carmichael and Colin Trevorrow's dialogue is spread a little thin. The main issue with Derek Connolly and Trevorrow story is the same issue as its predecessor, once you move them away from the West World-like Jurassic park setting or confines of a small Island the fear and intrigue is diluted. It 'jumped shark' with human cloning and even more so in Dominion especially durning the Malta underground dealing shenanigans. Unfortunately, it's simply too outlandish and over the top, rather than a dino-adventure, it's more messy spy thriller with dinosaurs.

There's wonderful cinematography from John Schwartzman, the effects are also impressive, the action is complimented by Michael Giacchino's music and John Williams themes. It's nice that they used the character of Dodgson, here played by Campbell Scott replacing Cameron Thor from Jurassic Park (1993). Both the Dr. Ellie Sattler and Dr. Alan Grant get fitting closure. Also we finally see what happened to the canister lost by Dennis Nedry in the original.

Overall, it's a wonderfully looking fun film, jam packed with dinosaur hi-jinx and show downs. But it just lacks the simplicity, also the emotional weight of the original trilogy; and Jurassic World to some extent. It's just not the direction maybe some viewers wanted it to go, to change the taste of Coca-cola means you have to change the recipe; and over the last two films they changed the taste of Coca-cola. Recommended with cola caution.

Holding Too Much Dominion Over Mediocrity
rgkarim11 June 2022
LIKES: The Comedy: The Jurassic Park series has always had some string of comedy sprinkled in the darker world of the survival pictures. Dominion goes a little more into this realm, working to make it very funny and sometimes in the modern style of more is better. Pratt and Goldblum are the primary haulers of the comedy, while the other characters sneak their own levels of laughs into the mix. Yet my favorite styles were some of the dinosaur moments and how the managed to make several of them have a little more human side and deliver that comedic punch to rock our worlds. Though forced a bit at times, the comedy really is decently done and feels back to being natural and well-placed like the first movies.

Lots of Dinosaurs: It's a movie about dinosaurs and well you get dinosaurs... where others have shown their cards and given you a few species to enjoy and get glimpses of, Dominion really makes this supposed final act, have all the dinosaurs that you could want in this short run time. While some of them are the classic monsters you remember, there are other species from various eras that arise from the shadows and most of them feel just as sinister and destructive as you hope for in this series. So for those tired of the typical thunder lizards, you'll be in for a treat at the variety the movie brought with it.

The Musical Score: Hands down another great lineage to this movie, the musical score is certainly one that still gives me goosebumps when I hear it boom over the speakers. Like the sound editing that brings the roars to life, the sixth part of the saga has the powerful orchestra work to add emotion to the scene and pull you into the full experience. Softer tones accompany or proceed the pounding orchestra blast that this series does super well. It's part of the movie theater experience worthy tone of this movie series and one of my favorite parts of the movie.

The Pace: While certainly not the target pace of the first film, Dominion manages to still keep the action going and keep things moving. For all the story elements this movie juggled, it did not do a half-bad job for me in them working it to remain entertaining. From the opening moments that sum up the events before to getting into the Dinosaur action and solutions, it really just keeps a steady pace without dawdling too much on the truth. Again, the result is an entertaining adventure for fans of the series to enjoy and just get more Dinosaur carnage and rampaging on the screen.

The Acting: While certainly not the most unique or Oscar worthy in terms of roles and performances, the movie's repertoire of actors and actresses accomplishes the fun I like to see in these movies. Pratt is Pratt, he's goofy, but action hero epic, as he does his best to tame the primitive and fearsome beasts that are on the screen. He's the typical hero role we've come to love in him, and he has some great moves to finish this series off. Howard is probably the one with the most dynamic range in this film, her character getting a lot more time and scenarios than other characters at this time. As a result, she accomplished much in her character's growth and ability, really selling the emotions for the most part and giving me more to like about Claire while avoiding going too far down the stoic warrior path. As for Dern, she's a master of her trade, and I liked the new Ellie that was still the same quality components we got in number one, but still adding some new qualities that shows what she has been doing for the last three decades. As for the rest of the group, they do a great job with the parts handed and there are too many to go through given how loaded the film is. However, the summary is: Neal is great if a bit underutilized, Sermon is funny and replays the role quite well, Wise is tough, funny, and reminiscent of the American pilot trope from Spielberg films, while Goldblum accomplishes much in that same steal the show moment you love.

The Character Use: While nowhere near perfect, Dominion does a better job than I intended of keeping the cast involved in the entire film, at least the human cast. With all sorts of characters to try and pull into one final act, you have a lot of stories, actors, and teams to try and keep ingrained in the tale. Old cast may not be the most involved at times, but hit at the moments that matter and give the loyal fans everything they need to wrap up this portion of the Jurassic World series, including laughs and a few tropes that you might be wanting to see. As for the new ones this part of the series, they get a lot more of the time and again accomplish the goal of expanding the story, whilst still being fun avatars to live through in this world.

The Chase Scene/Action At Times: The trailers showed an exciting scene of dinosaurs and bikes, and you know what... it accomplished it big time. I loved the race through the streets, a feeling of Mission Impossible meeting Dinos as they raced for survival in this CGI world. I absolutely loved this moment and felt it was the highlight of the action for this movie and the true climactic experience, if not a little cheesy at times. Other action scenes felt very part of the world, and there is a few big beast fights that you'll be wanting to see that really have some fun qualities to them, including one epic finish. As such, the action does accomplish its role for this series and should have the extreme fanatics stomping their feet in delight.

The Graphics: By far, the ability of studios to make dinosaurs come to life is still something that, to quote Laura Dern, "you never get used to!". For me, I love seeing the beasts come to life, finding the balance between computer graphic use and animatronics to bring these ancient creatures back to life. With modern technology, the computer work has never looked better in textures and stationary shots, while the robots are still impressive, but a little more artificial at times, though still doing a fantastic job of making them pop off the screen.

The Action At Times: Again, more beasts and humans, means a bit more of other qualities being scattered and the action is again one of those moments. Prior to the new trilogy, Jurassic Park's action was mostly about survival in the world of the largest carnivores. While some of that does exist, Dominion seems to have diluted most of it to the modern day action, leading to some great moments mentioned above, but also weaker elements you had hoped would be a bit more intense in the long run. The result is less intense action moments and feel like there are less stakes to be had.

The Subplots: Characters have to have arcs and backgrounds to be engaging right? Well, Jurassic World: Dominion does have that, only with so many characters in the mix they are a little diluted and bland. Both old and new have things they can certainly pursue, but sadly don't do well with everybody on the screen. The new pilot who lives life dangerously, Malcolm's story over the last two decades of what's happened with him, even Ellie to an extent all feel very simplistic given what it could have been. It's not horrible, and checks the box for complete, but for those invested in the characters, don't expect the most thought out character plots for others.

The Main Story: By far the weaker of the tales, was indeed the story of Jurassic World Dominion. Painting a very broad stroke and keeping all the characters in it, this movie is not quite the focused feature the others have been. While most merely just want a survival film filled with dinosaurs and more dinosaurs, others again want to be engaged with the film. Again, for me, this film diluted both and the great overarching story is a little more political story than actually engaging feature. The villain is simplified and boring, the solutions to the problems almost as dry and uncreative, as they simply work through things. Throw in the predictability, the lack of suspense, and the statistical probability of what is going to happen and the plot becomes less impressive in favor of the flash in a pan gimmick.

The Lack of Suspense and Terror: By far, the lack of suspense and terror is what I was missing in this film. Jurassic World has lost so much of the thing that drew us into the first series, the intensity of surviving the next encounter and how they got out, racking us with terror as the fake monsters tried to tear their way to food. For me, that feeling has been gone since number three, replaced with an almost action/drama feel that while it has it's good parts, is still not the same edge it once had. I did not find myself talking to the screen encouraging them to go, go, go like I once did and that was a bit sad for me really. It was this lack of intensity that II think was the weakest component of the movie and the lack of intensity is the component that really made the movie drawl in my case.

The VERDICT:

The supposed last installment of the great dinosaur movie was entertaining and fun, with the effects being the main thing to experience in theater. It juggles the cast well, makes for a fun use of multiple dinosaur species, and breaks open the music and technology to craft the world. It handles the cast decently well and keeps that engaging pace you want in a movie like this, devoid of any complex plot of processing. However, even the simple adventure like that lacks the bite of the original series, putting almost too much in one film that it spreads the quality across the two-hours unevenly and in many ways less than the potential it had. The biggest disappointment with me was in fact the lack of terror and suspense, this component almost washed out entirely given the predictability of the tale. So, factoring that in my scores of the movie are:

Action/Adventure/sci-fi: 7.0 Movie Overall: 6.0.

Time for this to go extinct
bankofmarquis10 June 2022
Like it was millions of years ago, the time of the dinosaurs is coming to a close. With JURASSIC WORLD DOMINION, we end the Jurassic World trilogy (after having the Jurassic Park trilogy) and it is high time we do so.

A retro-film (as I've been calling these nostalgia-flicks that bring back old actors/characters from previously beloved properties), JURARSSIC WORLD DOMINION is entertaining enough - but the creative brains behind this franchise is just running out of clever ways to put the same group of characters in danger of being eaten by a dinosaur.

Written by Emily Carmichael based on a story by Derek Connolly and Colin Trevorrow and Directed by Trevorrow (returning to helm this franchise after Directing the first Jurassic World flick, but not the 2nd), JURASSIC WORLD DOMINION follows our favorite bickering couple, Clare (Bryce Dallas Howard) and Owen (Chris Pratt) and their pseudo-pet Velociraptor, Blue as they, once again, go into the Jurassic World fighting a money-grubbing Corporate Billionaire who wants the genetic technology for his own, greedy purposes and not what might be for the good of all - the Earth, the Humans and the Dinosaurs. Along the way good ol' Alan Grant (Sam Neill), Ellie Sattler (Laura Dern) and Dr. Ian Malcolm (the always quirky Jeff Goldblum) are, somehow, shoe-horned into this story.

And that, ultimately, is the issue with Dominion, the script feels like an amalgam of characters that needed to be serviced and set-pieces that needed to be shown, but the overall story-line and character development (not that there is much here) is shoved to the side, so at the end the emotional connection to this film - and it's characters - is negligible.

What little character interest there is here is based solely on the charisma of the actors and they are...good enough. Pratt, of course, is able to carry the center of this flick as Owen Grady - but he doesn't seem to be occupying the center square with the twinkle in his eye that he had in the first Jurassic World film. Bryce Dallas Howard is plucky enough as Clare, but this actress has been gaining traction lately as a "go-to" Director (like her father, Ron Howard) and that is probably a better career trajectory for her. Sam Neill and Laura Dern are "game enough" in what they are asked to do, but they both look just a bit tired of running around in front of green screen dinosaurs. Only Jeff Goldblum shines as Ian Malcolm and that's because Trevorrow, wisely, decides to let Goldblum be Goldblum - odd and quirky.

Of the other actors in this film, DeWanda Wise (FATHERHOOD) really shines as a pilot who helps out the gang. On the other hand, Dichen Lachman (SEVERENCE) is completely wasted as a "top-notch" henchman that is pretty inept. However, it was good to see Omar Sy (who was in the first JURASSIC WORLD movie and then became a star thanks to his work on the French TV show LUPINE - which is terrific, by the way) back in the fold as it was good to see Campbell Scott back up on the big screen as the villain of the piece - a role that he brings an interesting twist to but, ultimately, the role leads to nowhere.

And that's the issue with this film, the characterizations lead to nowhere, for Trevorrow focuses most of his attention on the battle scenes and the scares - and while not all of them are exciting and unusual, I did find myself jumping in my seat on more than one occasion and there is one scene with Bryce Dallas Howard escaping a dino in a swamp that was pretty intense.

Go see JURASSIC WORLD DOMINION if you've seen the other 5 - you've already invested this much time, you might as well complete the series. But, this film really brings nothing new and is, ultimately, less than what one hopes for in this type of film.

Letter Grade: B-

Cinematography & Editing - Bland framing and long cuts make it like a made for TV production with lazy camera movements and composition. 2:1 aspect ratio okay to capture size of dinosaurs, but framing too zoomed in on actors giving a lack of feel of their environment and mostly see the actors. Also, actors look like giants, should have zoomed out a little to consider for big screen, not a TV. That height zoom more useful in anamorphic aspect ratio where the environment is covered on the left and right spaces.

Dinosaurs & CGI - Mostly good CGI and details, but some looked too cartoony and behaved too human like ala Disney and such. While some had good predatory animation and somewhat natural animal movements and mannerism, some had awkward and stiff control of their bodies as if a human had possessed the dinosaurs and figuring out how to use its limbs. The interactions of the alpha dinosaurs were awkwardly lost and poorly choreographed. The film trailers with outdoor cinemas and "documentary" wildlife feature are purely promotional (i.e. Misleading)

Story - The redux on Blue and Maisie as a material part of "purpose" and their revelations and throwbacks are uninspiring. The "evil corp" doing woke detriment to the world is also so bland. Nothing intelligent. The "oooo" something behind the scenes is going on that is slowly unraveled to the audience is so poorly filmed and revealed that it was almost like little children playing make believe. Everything seems poorly established and shot (again with lazy cinematography, cuts/editing, dull framing and timing like a daytime drama). There was an essence of espionage and its relevant rush action, but I felt it out of place and too "copy and paste".

Conclusion - This film lacks direction, ideation and inspiration, full of stale recycled formulae poorly executed. To the die hard fans, just watch it to scratch that dodgy itch, see some eye candy and be able to say you did it, but expect to be disappointed to a point of disgust. I loved the return of Sam Neill as Alan Grant, Laura Seen as Ellie Sattler, and Jeff Goldblum as Ian Malcolm. They were all good and I liked seeing them and the Jurassic World cast work together in the 3rd act against the main villain dinosaur.

The action scenes are fun to watch and there are suspenseful scenes involving some dinosaurs. The dinosaurs look good and have nice effects, I also saw some interesting looking dinosaurs with unique designs that look cool.

The big problem of the movie is the main plot and how it changes a certain story that was in the past film. I thought the beginning of the movie was slow, but it starts to pick up once it starts to go through the 2nd act and the 3rd act.

The ending of the movie was confusing, and I did not know how we were led to it. Jurassic World: Dominion (2022) has an ok ending the movie series and was better than the last movie, but I think this could have been better if they gave us more of what we wanted and did not have a side plot in the way.

How the mighty have fallen...
manticore-6468211 June 2022
Jurassic Park has been my favourite film since it had first come out. It is a perfect masterpiece, that overcomes any flaw by grabbing you emotionally, as well as still being one of the most entertaining movies ever made. The sequels, while not being nearly as good, all delivered on the dinosaur action and had some good moments (the action in Lost World and 3 at times rivaled the action in that original movie, and World had some excellent ideas and moments of awe). But each one carried with it a little less of the magic than the last one. Here at Jurassic World Dominion that magic is gone. Its been flushed down the toilet!

The film has 2 stories. Owen and Claire are rescuing a kidnapped girl and baby raptor. And then Alan Grant, Ellie Setler and Ian Malcolm are doing some espionage to stop an evil corporation from doing some dodgy stuff. Oh, also there are dinosaurs...sometimes, when the script needs them.

There is no sugar coating it. This was terrible. Absolutely terrible! Fallen Kingdom, while not being a film I like, had a weird charm to it; great visuals, good direction and a Corman-esk final act. This, I appreciate now, elevated it from being garbage, even if it had none of what made the original good in the first place. So, and you read right, Dominion lacks what made Fallen Kingdom 'good'.

Other than the nostalgia of seeing Sam Neill, Laura Dern and Jeff Goldbloom together again, this film has nothing going for it. It is completely soulless. The story doesn't work, and often uses action scenes to make it look like we are going somewhere. Most of the new actors are giving horrible performances. The music sucks, unless they use the original score in poorly placed moments. It is cripplingly boring on top of it all.

The rest of the series coasted on dino action when all else failed. This was why I went to see this one. But even that is a let down. There are many types of dinosaurs here, but the dinosaurs feel secondary to everything else that is going on. The action rings hollow. Not to spoil, but the ending action scene left so little impact, it was shocking. You can't even enjoy the effects this time as they are easily the worst of the whole series. The CGI is fine, if a little wonky at times, but the animatronics are worse than those on the theme park ride. Stan Winston will be rolling in his grave.

There are moments here and there. A scene involving a dinosaur with enormous claws was genuinely well done. Sam Neill and the others are great to watch. A tunnel scene with the dilophosaurus was creepy. And there are a good number of moments that had me laughing at the stupidity and absurdity of it all.

In the end, that first film being my favourite of all time and the rest being good (or at least dumb) fun, I really didn't like this one. I am unsure as to whether I hate it or not, but that I am contemplating this, it is just sad to me. I felt like I was watching my copy of Jurassic Park burn. I don't care if they make any more, this is the last one for me.

Time to go the way of the dinosaurs
stilloopless110 June 2022
The summer box office continues to heat up with this weeks' release of Jurassic World Dominion, the sixth and final installment of the popular movie franchise based on Michael Crichton's novels. Twenty-nine years after Jurassic Park, dinosaurs are living and hunting alongside humans taxing the fragile balance of nature all over the world. Well, that's what we're led to believe is the setup for Jurassic World Dominion, however, the movie we actually get is an altogether different beast.

Jurassic World Dominion is essentially two different films with the original trio of Sam Neil (Alan Grant), Ellie Sattler (Laura Dern), and Jeff Goldblum (Ian Malcolm) reuniting in one story (the more interesting of the two in my opinion) and Chris Pratt (Owen Grady) and Bryce Dallas Howard (Claire Dearing) picking up and continuing their story from Jurassic World Fallen Kingdom. Eventually the two stories meet and everything is brought to a conclusion.

Sadly, the conclusion, as well as the ride leading up to it is far from spectacular or overall satisfying.

The pacing in Jurassic World Dominion is clunky and uneven, particularly in the beginning. Many of the themes are heavy handed and preachy to the point of making you feel you're sitting in a lecture hall. Oddly enough, Ian's actual lecture in the film is more entertaining and thought provoking than the bludgeoning messaging throughout the rest of the film. The call backs to previous films in many cases are stale. With the exception of the original Big Three, the returning characters are lifeless (in Pratt's case the film plays more like a contractual obligation) and uninspired. BD Wong's Dr. Wu takes an unexpected turn and the resolution of his story line feels unearned. New characters aren't fleshed out and act more as props to get from point a to point b than characters.

Worse still, Jurassic World Dominion, is a dinosaur movie that has little to do with dinosaurs. Again, Goldblum's Ian says it best when he goes off on the seduction of dinos excusing what's going on. A note that the writers should of taken when sussing out the story. Dinosaurs are freely living among humans, what's that like? Dunno, it's glossed over save for a few references. I mean at one point in this 2 hour 26 minute film you go a good half hour to forty minutes without seeing or hearing ANYTHING about the dinosaurs.

Serious bait and switch as well as a major disappointment.

The biggest saving grace of Dominion is the legacy characters, especially Goldblum's Ian. The wit, charm, and humor is classic. All three actors seem to be having a blast and it shows and you feel it ever time they're on screen. When you get the dinosaurs they look amazing. These bad boys never fail to delight.

All told Jurassic World Dominion looks great, has some shining moments, but ultimately is lifeless. If this is what the franchise has to offer, it's time to let it go the way of actual dinosaurs.

Jurassic World Dominion gets a disappointing 5 from me.

I walked into my local Odeon today, for an evening of cinematic entertainment, and walked out of it with a headache.

The first hour of the film is setup. Yes, the entire first hour just sets up the story. We felt like we were stuck in the writers' room, and had various versions of the script thrown at us. The VFX were quite impressive. The sound design, not as much. There was so much screaming, screeching, metal bending, vehicles crashing, airplanes getting blown out of the sky, and all that noise kept going for so long. Two hours of this type of noise, almost non-stop, and with almost no music to give our ears a break. Pretty sure that's where the headache came from.

The plot is quite thin, but I didn't really mind that since, come on, it's Jurassic World. I did mind that the jump scares were noisy instead of scary. I did mind that the film didn't make me fear for the characters' lives, not only because the dangers they were in were always so out of proportions they should have died 10000 times, but also because it didn't let me care about the characters. Sam Neal could have been gobbled up on the, I think, 45 minute mark, when he showed up, and I would have probably been fine with that.

Also, look out for the scene where Baddie#1235 is lying down, both hands being eaten up by 2 separate dinosaurs, and still has the mental capacity to give our protagonist the information he needs, instead of screaming his head off in terror and pain.

We gave up at the point where they managed to get all the characters together, more than 2 hours in, and after a long, long, escape scene, they got to yet more exposition on how they'd escape. In that moment, me and my friend looked at each other, realised there was probably an extra 40 minutes of film, grabbed our stuff and left.

This film is empty calories. There are no jokes, no cute quotes, no sense of wonder, not even the thrill/slight terror of watching humans getting hunted by dinosaurs. Save your money, watch it at home. Save your braincells, bypass it entirely.

Jurassic World: Dominion (2022) is a movie we watched as a family in theatres last night. The storyline follows a world that is trying to adjust to dinosaurs being a regular part of every day life. Meanwhile an evil organization looks to exploit circumstances by creating genetically engineered locusts to destroy the Earths food so you need to rely on them to survive...oh, and they want to steal Hammond's cloned niece. It will take the heroes from every movie of the Jurassic Park series to save the day.

This movie is directed by Colin Trevorrow (Jurassic World) and stars Chris Pratt (Guardians of the Galaxy), Jeff Goldblum (The Fly), Sam Neill (Event Horizon), Bryce Dallas Howard (The Help), Mamoudou Athie (Uncorked) and Laura Dern (Blue Velvet).

This movie, unfortunately, it's about the same as Jurassic World: Kingdom. The dinosaurs and special effects are awesome. There's some tremendous species of dinosaurs and dinosaur battles, especially the last one. Unfortunately for the storyline, it reminded me of John Wick 3, just an excuse for dinosaur scenes like that John Wick was just an excuse for action scenes with a flimsy cliché storyline. There were also too many subplots going on in here - some were fun and entertaining (black market and underground trade was well done, locusts and cloned child not so much). The acting was fine but the cast could have been way better utilized with better writing.

Overall this was a fun popcorn flick as long as you go in with the right mind set. Think of it like watching Fast and Furious, Transformers and John Wick; no it's not going to be a good movie, but the dinosaurs are cool. I would score this a 6/10 and recommend seeing it once.

Action-Packed Film Filled With Great Comedy And Strong Actor Performances.
rannynm13 June 2022
Bigger and scarier dinosaurs, heart-pounding sound effects, and plot twists mixed with plenty of adventures are just what you can expect from Jurassic World Dominion! From the beginning to the end of the movie, there are tons of action-packed scenes to keep you literally jumping for more. Fans of the Jurassic Park franchise will not be disappointed.

Jurassic World Dominion centers around two different storylines. On one hand, Maisie Lockwood (Isabella Sermon), a teenager, who happens to be a clone of her biological mother, is kidnapped and taken to a company called Biosyn to become a science experiment so scientists can learn how her biological mother created her. On the other hand, her parents, Claire Dearing (Bryce Dallas Howard) and Owen Grady (Chris Pratt), set out on an adventure to rescue her. Ellie Sattler (Laura Dern) is suspicious of the works of Biosyn and its animal experiments, as well as its attempt to take over the food chain. She brings in Alan Grant (Sam Neill) to help her stop Biosyn from taking over. The two storylines eventually combine for one suspenseful adventure that happens to take place all while dinosaurs are threatening the characters' existence.

The main characters in this film are Maisie, Claire, Owen, Alan, Ellie, and Dr. Ian Malcolm (Jeff Goldblum). There are references and character appearances from other movies in the Jurassic Park franchise. I enjoyed seeing how characters from different parts of the film join together to save Maisie and end up trying to save each other and become a family while working together. There are some funny scenes throughout the film, and I loved seeing the characters communicating with the dinosaurs and even making them promises. The movie takes you on an emotional rollercoaster as you root for the good guys to not only survive but to win.

This film touches on family and whether or not dinosaurs and humans can co-exist. You'll have to watch the movie to find out. While I highly enjoyed Jurassic World Dominion, this film may not be suitable for people who have certain fears/anxieties or even suffer from PTSD. Parents should look out for scenes with extreme violence, gory deaths, and loads of jump scares.

I give Jurassic World Dominion 4 out of 5 stars and recommend it for kids ages 12 to 18, plus adults. This film roars into theaters on June 10, 2022. By Tiana S., KIDS FIRST!

Jurassic World: Dominion is the third (and probably the last) instalment in the Jurassic World trilogy. This movie entails how the world is going to cope with the arrival of dinosaurs in our own environment as well as the power of genetics. We are introduced to not only how our society is coping with the arrival of dinosaurs but also how the dinosaurs are coping with us.

Although it has an enormous amount of cameos and call-backs from the original Jurassic Park trilogy, it just feels like it is missing something, almost like the spark that fuelled this 6 movie franchise. I love Jurassic Park, as well as the original characters, but it was missing something. However, I do feel that it was a bit rushed in places and was not too dinosaur-heavy as the previous films. This film is basically entailing the grand scheme of things, how our society and environment is changing due to the arrival of dinosaurs and how we can co-exist with them. After 5 films we finally get to see dinosaurs co-existing with humans. I think this is a good finale (?) to the Jurassic Park franchise, but it was missing something, still a really enjoyable film with lots of nostalgia for die-hard fans.

Everyone's unreasonable expectations are clouding the reviews of this movie

Warning: Spoilers
3 out of 6 found this helpful. Was this review helpful? Sign in to vote.

85/100

Firstly, this is in no way comparable to TROS. Sure there are parallels, last of the 'saga' returning characters, but unlike TROS, these characters aren't shoehorned into the movie like Lando was. If anything this movie resembles TFA with its returning cast.

Dominion is criticised for its meshing of two separate plots together and whilst I agree that there was too much preparation for the merge of the stories rather than having a fleshed-out final act, I don't see it as a huge problem with this film.

For me the worst part about the film was the soundtrack, a lot of the music just seemed off, and as stated in IGN's review, the best bits of sound came from edited versions of John Williams' score. The score lets this movie down quite a bit. And a few sloppy lines of dialogue from the actors/actresses are noticeable but apart from that, I found this movie pretty fun and interesting.

It's not what people expected from this 'finale' but I like the idea and the direction they went for this movie. The characters feel right for the movie. Franklin's character, albeit in a smaller role has proved a massive glow-up from his fallen kingdom role. He became likable. Maisy is hit or miss but I was fine with her portrayal and the new characters, especially Ramsey were great.

As for the dinosaur scenes, I think the vast increase in new dinosaurs was awesome! So many new faces and creatures, a lot of Giganotosaurus action which was great to see, and even Rexy got some good screen time. It's a shame they cut the prologue to this movie, but the film is quite long so it is understandable, maybe they'll have some more deleted scenes on the DVD release.

Both the VFX and the Practical effects are well done, for the most part, you won't notice any of the lesser quality CGI unless you really slow the movie down and this is just not fair to criticise because why would you slow down a fast-paced action scene to .25 of a second.

Overall, this film will divide opinions, I know many aren't pleased with the film, especially critics. But if you want an entertaining, unique, and new take on the Jurassic saga, this is the first movie since JPIII that attempts something that isn't a complete remaster of an already produced story. I think that this movie is good, it has flaws but for what we get, it's great. It's better than fallen kingdom (a movie I actually enjoyed) and for that, it ranks as my third favourite movie of the 6.

Too much and also too little.
Darwinskid13 June 2022
Like most who were born in the 1990's I grew up with the original Jurassic Park and would watch it almost endlessly on VHS. It not only entertained, but also sparked my interest in all things dinosaurs and was one of the movies that made me want to be a filmmaker. I am happy that even as I have grown older, and my cinematic tastes have matured I still am able to rate the film highly. I would echo with most regarding the sequels and that they all left much to be desired. The Lost World is entertaining and has some nice world building and spectacle but lacks the charm of its predecessor. Jurassic Park III is essentially one long action set piece with a storyline that is neither interest or very exciting. Jurassic World is essentially the first movie on a larger scale but still is charming and entertaining. Fallen Kingdom has a nice set up but after the island is engulfed into ash it essentially becomes a monster-in-the-house kind of movie. Dominion I am sorry to say is not the complete home run a fan has been hoping for in 29 years.

Dominion has the ambitious task of concluding this trilogy of Jurassic installments, finish the arcs for the new and old casts of characters, and ultimately conclude the franchise as a whole. It aims high but doesn't grasp at the greatness it's hoping to achieve. There is too much going on in the plot that often it feels like two different movies spliced into one. There are so many concepts, themes, characters, and set-ups that it honestly comes across like somebody edited down an entire season of television into a two-and-a-half-hour film - To be honest, I think I would have preferred a series over a movie given how much Colin Trevorrow sets out to do in such a span of time. The cast all do fine, everyone is charismatic, the imagery is often dynamic and fantastic, and the spectacle is often incredible to witness on the big screen, though the wonderment of the original and even The Lost World and to an extent Jurassic World feels almost entirely lost.

Watching the film, I couldn't help but think that Trevorrow learned a lot from his experience with working on the ninth episode of Star Wars and how Kathleen Kennedy and Lucasfilm/Disney. Mismanaged and letdown legions of fans, and when he left and set out to try and avoid the pitfalls of The Rise of Skywalker by trying to give everyone as much as he thought they wanted; he succeeds to an extent, but the overlong runtime and constant juggle of storylines and characters make the more satisfying moments lacking total and complete emotional impact. I don't blame him for trying, especially given that Fallen Kingdom wasn't as well liked as Jurassic World and trying to make a picture that pleases every fan is satisfying as well. I wish it had worked out in his favor, but alas.

I managed to do something I haven't done in a long time, and that's not see a single movie trailer or preview going into Jurassic World Dominion. Which I am thankful for that I was able to enjoy a lot of the scenes that would have been spoiled in the trailers. The movie was watchable, enjoyable to see everyone together, great to see all the dinosaurs, how they would effect everyday human life, and felt the right length, but that's about it. Seemed like everyone of our old favorites was only fronting the effort and there wasn't much energy.

Story line doesn't really make sense. A lot unnecessary plot holes. Obsession with the clone girl from the last movie and as always, Raptor DNA. Never really explained how a few dozen dinosaurs escaping in California are able to spread world wide other than "illegal breeders" and "poaching".

They do the same tired Trex vs another apex predator rivalry fight yet this is the worst match up of all the movies. They make the Giganotosaurus to be the bad guy vs the Trex for no reason whatsoever.

The entire movie revolves around genetically modifying giant prehistoric locust and releasing them on the world and how the crazy Steve Jobs megalomaniac was the only one that didn't see how bad that was. Sadler and Grant need to get a sample from inside to prove the connection? Really? No government in the world could investigate or make the connection that the company involved with giant prehistoric dinosaur DNA might also be the ones responsible for the giant genetically modified locusts?

I will saw that the variety dinosaurs we saw were great to watch. #Justice for the deer that got yeeted for no reason while minding its own business.

More of the same missteps as two previous Jurassic World sequels
Airman8710 June 2022
I had hopes this was a different film than the other Trevorrow Jurassic World sequels, especially with the legacy Jurassic Park cast members making a comeback. I was wrong. The opening scene immediately sets the tone by spoon-feeding the audience Chris Pratt wrangling and taming a wild dinosaur. There is no cleverly sagacious writing here, just more explosions and dinosaur fight club from Trevorrow. The plot almost works, but feels too synthetic in having no point but to involve original cast members. The fundamental issue with the film is that, for all the grasping at nostalgia, the story is simply not set in the same world as where we want to see or remember the characters in.

While the girls and bicurious Disney fans in love with Chris Pratt may like the movie, the older adults who vividly remember and cherish the first Jurassic Park as one of their favorite movies will be glad this franchise has finally been euthanized.

Spares no expense at dinosaur action, but falls short of its own premise
ObsessiveCinemaDisorder14 June 2022
Jurassic World Dominion, the third entry in the Jurassic World series and sixth film in the overall franchise, unites the current and original cast together for a big symphonic finish.

In the words of John Hammond, the film spares no expense at delivering spectacle and thrills. Unfortunately, Dominion buckles under its own weight from too many characters and the story ultimately falls under the law of diminishing returns from having nothing new to say.

At the end of Jurassic World Fallen Kingdom, dinosaurs have been let loose and are free roaming across the Earth, living alongside humans. I was expecting Dominion to explore this fresh untapped narrative.

Unfortunately, that's not the story we get. Dominion is another story of corporate greed about genetically-bred locusts that's endangering the world's food supply. Maisie Lockwood, the clone daughter of Sir Benjamin Lockwood from the previous film, may hold the key to saving the world.

Imagine buying a ticket to see dinosaurs. You see the movie and you're like, "Hey man, where are my dinosaurs?" The movie goes, "Look! Locusts!"

It is disappointing on some level. From the trailers, I was imagining the old and current cast teaming up, saving both humans and dinosaurs from each other across the globe, ensuring peace between the two like X-men, but with dinosaurs. "D-men", if you will. The script practically writes itself.

Do not fret though. There are plenty of dinosaurs in Dominion despite not being the narrative focus. The dinosaurs are obstacles that the characters have to survive through in the film's numerous set pieces.

The action is well done. The standout sequence is a Mission Impossible-like motorcycle chase with raptors through the streets of Malta. New dinosaurs also provide some nail-biting suspenseful moments.

There are too many characters; that is 6 lead characters, and 5 supporting characters all fighting for screentime. The two characters that I cared about, and wished the film focused more on, were Sam Neil and Laura Dern's characters. One of the biggest disappointments in Jurassic Park 3 was learning that Alan Grant and Ellie Satler split up. Dominion attempts to mend that with a love story that it doesn't devote enough time towards.

Dr. Ian Malcolm's part was disappointing. Even though he had an active role, Jeff Goldblum had nothing to react to or anything clever to say. His performance felt off as it seemed like he took an extra beat than needed.

The Jurassic World films are in a repetitive story loop that the Fox's X-men franchise was once in. Similar to Magneto, Dr. Henry Wu, the true villain of the franchise, is always conveniently let go to keep the story going and for the same conflict to repeat. Dr. Wu should be branded as a known international criminal and jailed in a psychiatric ward by now for the havok he was brought in the last 3 films.

Jurassic World Dominion was advertised as the end of the new trilogy. There just wasn't any finality to any of it. You'll remember the action scenes but ultimately forget what happened story-wise.
