The motorcycle chase through a foreign country, whilst being chased by Gaga's laser Dino's, to jumping onto the moving plane (which I'm throughly impressed with him knowing exactly where to go to find this said plane in a place they have never, ever been to before) and of course, right in the nick of time! Then he survives the airplane crash, the fall through the ice with the chicken raptor that is clearly an avid swimmer, the countless encounters with the "apex predators" yadda yadda boring boring.

Does time and distance not exist in this new dino/human sharing world? Go from the woods of Oregon or whatever, to DC, or whatever, to the streets of Malta within a day? Then the plane crash, to deep in the jungle of dino infested woods to find his woman, within...what 10,20 min? The whole cast is able to get, what looks to be a 1-2 day hike at minimum, without breaking a sweat.

Did anyone realize with in the first 5 movies Dr. Wu and Dr. Sadler were horrible actors?? I didn't.

The locust? Why was this not called Locust: World Domination? They have about the same amount of screen time, if not more than all the Dino's combined. And the whole movie basically centers around them. The Dino's are just background actors.

They glossed right over the fact A WOMAN WAS ABLE TO GET HERSELF PREGNANT!? What!?

How does a young girl, aged 10 - living with 2 Americans STILL have her thick British accent 4 years later?? What!?

Didn't the last movie explain she was a clone of Lockwoods granddaughter THAT DIED IN A CAR CRASH when she was a child? Not a prolific, scholar of a scientist that spoke at colleges, and was able to replace a chromosome in her daughter - THAT SHE CONCEIVED ALL ALONE - and eradicate a full on deadly disease in her. Why was this hidden? Why could this girl not know this?

What was good about this movie you may ask? Baby Blue. Baby Blue was flippin adorable. Period.

Do yourself a favor and save 2.5 hours of your life, from this jumbled up mess.

"JURASSIC PARK: DOMINION" REVIEW
Mr-Topshotta17 June 2022
Directed by Colin Trevorrow. Starring Chris Pratt as "Owen Grady", Bryce Dallas Howard as "Claire Dearing". Which starred in the last three films. They also brought back Laura Dern as "Ellie Sattler", Sam Neill as "Alan Grant" and Jeff Goldblum as "Ian Malcolm from the original three films.

This is the third and final film in the "Jurassic World" franchise. Wrapping up the entire franchise as a whole. Now in this film "Claire" and "Owen" are hiding out and taking up a parent role with the clone of "Maisie Lockwood" played by Isabella Sermon. The company that helped make her wants her back. "Claire" and "Owen" also trying to do their part in wrangling in wild dinasours and bringing them to "Lewis Dodgson" played by Campbell Scott. A Tim Cook doppelgänger in the film.

Because of the events from the last film dinosaurs are every where. They are apart of normal life now. Which also made an extreme black market for them on top of the rare breeding and genetic tampering. "Lewis" company "Biotech" made a Sanctuary that the dinasaurs can go to and be safe. While he also does leading edge stuff to cure diseases with his company. But the genius billionaire has a little more to him then the naked eye can see.

After "Blue" the Velociraptor "Owen" trained in the earlier films and has a bond with, had a child. Now "Maisie" and "Blue" child are in grave danger because of their uniqueness. Some other shady stuff is going on from "Biotech" which brings the original cast together with the help of a inside man "Ramsay Cole" played by Mamoudou Athie.

"Owen" and "Claire" receive some help from their old friends "Dr. Zia", "Franklin", and "Barry". Played by Daniella Pineda, Justice Smith, and Omar Sy. Along with a new friend they picked up on the way "Kayla Watts" played by DeWanda Wise from "She's Gotta Have it".

Some how the old and the new mash up together. Of course finding themselves knee deep in dinosaur trouble.

"Jurassic World: Dominion" was a good bad film or a bad good film. Whichever way you want to put it. They put all the money in the CGI and left no money for the script. The Transitions were really bad. Some of the plot points made no sense or were just bad. Even connecting characters in the film. It looks and feels like we don't know a good way to get these people in one location so we're just going to write anything. I felt like no effort went into the script.

I say all that to say the graphics were amazing. The action scenes were gripping and fun. I felt like I was in the film and Velociraptors were chasing me. Those scenes were amazing. The volume and sheer power of the bigger dinosaurs just amazed me. This film was so thrilling and entertaining.

If it involved humans majority of the time it was odd and scenes that made no sense. They were forcing the fact they combined both of the franchises. They Re-enacted multiple scenes from the original films in this film. At first it was really cool. But after the third one it was like ok I get it. I see what your doing there. I loved when we first saw "Grant" and "Ellie" but they took all the nostalgia out of it because of how hard they were forcing things.

Overall you should see this film on the biggest screen possible. Just know that the action is great and the dinosaurs look so good they'll feel real. You will be entertained, but the script is very bad. By the time your losing focus and coming to the realization this makes no sense something cool happens to take your mind off of how bad the transitions are. Oh and you can't forget the "Where's Waldo" of the franchise "Dr. Henry Wu played by BD Wong. They were wrong for how they ended that characters storyline. I give this film three mor fires 🔥🔥🔥.

#CosmoandtheMovieWithin #CosmoMovieBlog #CosmoLanier #JurassicParkDominion.

I am a huge Jurassic fan. I had my doubts about this movie going into it. I was sure the dialogue would be cheesy, the plot rushed and riddled with holes. Trevorrow is a good director, not so much a good screenwriter. I was anxious about the Malta scenes. Worried about there being too many characters.

That being said..... it all worked for me.

Comparing all these movies to the OG is where the problem lies. Everyone criticizes these newer films for not being the original one. But we've already HAD the original Jurassic Park. If there's another original, it can't be THE original. I don't know what people expect to happen in a situation where dinosaurs are literally everywhere. Could there have been more focus on peoples' everyday interactions with said dinosaurs and fewer interactions with giant locusts? Sure.

I liked the dialogue much more than I thought I would. The original cast worked pretty well for me here. I enjoyed the action. I actually felt connected to Owen and Claire for the first time in this film. Owen wasn't as stone-faced this film as he was the first two. Really enjoyed Dodgson. The music was great.

All in all, this is my new favorite film from the JW trilogy, whether or not it lives up to the expectations of others.

Dinosaurs are swept away to the sidelines as background details and decorations who pop up once in a while to say 'boo'. All we see here is a few more of the same familiar thrills and chills, but less epic, and with less to tell. Everything is so rushed with so many sprawling story beats, there's no moment to really soak in the suspense, dread, or beauty of a dinosaur. The writing and excuse to gather the gangs of characters together feels contrived. More of the same. Fun to watch, but underwhelming. I can just say I'm relieved the second trilogy is over. I only hope the next one finds a way.

Bandwagon reviews are saying it sucks, but it doesn't
danniemann11 June 2022
Look, obviously there's no comparison to the first film; it was nearly perfect, and this one has flaws. Still, it's by far the best of the sequels.

The dinosaurs look and feel incredible, and in this film they are everywhere. There are a couple main story threads that bring the main characters together, and one is more interesting than the other, but both hold your attention- and once the main characters are together, there is great chemistry there.

They didn't bring the old characters in for a quick cameo at the end, either, they are integral to the plot and drive things forward in their own right.

Jeff Goldblum, particularly, is just so entertaining to watch.

Also, it's nonsense to say this movie is "woke" just because they added a young black female character to the cast. She was a good character. A "Han Solo type" pilot who doesn't want to get involved but can't help herself.

Then the other half are mad that Chris Pratt was allowed to be in this film even though he's been publicly open about his faith- it must be exhausting to try to entertain people these days.

I brought my 13 year old son to this and I'm so glad I did. This film was a massive spectacle and at the end it felt like we had just finished something special. The long runtime flew by.

I don't know what some reviewers were expecting- perhaps the first film again- this isn't that. But it's fun and tense and amazing. I think it's become in fashion to bash these films (and the last one may have deserved it) but this one is very good.

A strong conclusion to the Jurassic Park / World-Series
raven-1188111 June 2022
Last night I went to see "Jurassic World 3 - A New Age" at the cinema. Here's my personal impression of the movie.

Briefly to the starting position of the story (minimal spoilers)

The plot begins three years after the events of Jurassic World 2. Dinos have conquered the black market and have spread around the world in this way. This has turned life around the world upside down and both humans and animals must now live in coexistence with the new "neighbor", whether they like it or not. Of course, this again calls both poachers, hunters and conservationists on the plan, but of course also corporations who want to make their profit from it or who take advantage of the dinos to make medical advances with the help of their DNA. But as always, there is of course more to a large corporation than meets the eye. This then also calls Dr. Ellie Sattler on the scene, who analyzes a new life-threatening plague: gigantic locusts, which were obviously created artificially and are spreading further and further and eating up all the food. She enlists the help of Dr. Alan Grant and Ian Malcolm to uncover a mystery. Meanwhile, Owen Grady, Claire Dearing along with Maisie Lockwood live in a deserted area in a forest cabin to hide and protect Maisie because she is still wanted. Some dangerous people are after her. So much for the beginning and the starting point of the movie. (End of spoilers)

The story is of course both trashy and rather flat, the characters remain quite pale, but that's what the series is known for. So I don't blame the film for that at all. I watch such movies because they are supposed to entertain and not because of their profundity, complexity or heaviness.

Actors / Characters

Owen Grady (Chris Pratt) is as likable as ever. I like his character and I like his manner. Pratt plays his role solidly as always. Pratt may be an actor who mostly plays himself and he's not as changeable now as a Leonardo DiCaprio, but he doesn't have to be. We also loved Arnie or Willis not because of their acting talent, but because of their style and their very own character. It's the same with Tom Cruise or Dwayne Johnson. And so it is with Chris Pratt. Owen Grady may be a flat and one-dimensional character, but such characters are also allowed (even must exist) in such trashy movies. Grady is simply the savior of the need, the helper who is always there when he is needed most.

Claire Dearing (Bryce Dallas Howard) is also as likable as ever. She is the animal/dinosaur protector par excellence and wants to prevent injustice to them at all costs. I buy this one. Otherwise, her character remains pale and superficial as well.

Then there is Maisie Lockwood (Isabella Sermon), the artificially created "clone" of Charlotte Lockwood. She is quite possibly the most complex character in the film and you learn more and more about her and her creation as the plot progresses. This is interesting and exciting and adds to my interest in the plot. The fact that there are then dangerous people after her raises even more questions than it provides answers. Isabelle Sermon plays this role wonderfully believably and I really like this character. If more films are made at some point, I think she should take the lead role.

Dr. Ellie Sattler (Laura Dern) is still the old and level-headed woman who questions many things and who takes a central role in the plot. Laura Dern still plays her character confidently and believably.

Dr. Alan Grant (Sam Neill) assists Dr. Sattler in her investigation and is still the stubborn maverick. He and Sattler have great chemistry and you can tell they got along well on set as well. Sam Neill also still plays his character very believably and I always enjoy seeing him as an actor.

Ian Malcolm (Jeff Goldblum) is of course also back in the cast and is once again allowed to utter wonderfully wacky, profound and philosophical phrases. He's still a great character with his wacky manner and charisma. I like him. And his scenes are always great and contrast with the serious situation.

Seeing all three of the old characters together again, and even as leads, is really pure nostalgia and was also sensibly integrated into the plot.

The antagonists are again just pull-off characters, but that's only half bad, because they serve their purpose to advance the plot and give the protagonists a task.

Then there's a new addition: Kayla Watts (DeWanda Wise). She is a pilot and smuggler/mercenary. Her character is quite pale, but also sympathetic. She's a bit like the female Han Solo in Jurassic World.

Also nice to have Omar Sy alias Barry Sembène back, who now works for the CIA.

Dinos / CGI Animations / Action Scenes

Dinos are common in this finale and and appear in a wide variety of species.

The CGI animations are very well done in my eyes and the dinos mostly look very believable and move really great. The integration into the moving image is very well done, so that only rarely the feeling of a "foreign body" arises.

Really great class is the much higher creepiness and thrill factor in this finale of the trilogy. In the second half of the film, the characters come up against dangerous and deadly dinosaurs time and again and have to hide from them, sneak past them, run away or face them. This makes for an enormous amount of thrills and suspense.

The first half of the film, on the other hand, is more dialogue-heavy, serving more to build the plot and show the new world. But to lighten things up, there are one or two fast-paced action scenes here as well. There is also a motorcycle chase with raptors through a city. I especially liked that one because it was so well edited, staged and filmed, and it's also just exciting and entertaining.

I also love how the new world where humans and dinos coexist was depicted and staged. Playing children being harassed by Compsognathus dinosaurs, sauropods interfering with agriculture or other dinos showing up everywhere or even attacking and eating humans at times. I really liked this depiction of the new coexistence.

Camera / Scenery / Editing

As briefly mentioned, I really like the camera work and there are a lot of great shots and takes. There isn't constant shaky cam, but the scenes were captured well and you always keep a good view of what is happening. Creepy moments were also captured great. I also liked the editing. Not too many hard and fast cuts, but often quite long cuts at a stretch.

Music

As always, the music consists of both old and new pieces. However, I was so captivated by the film that I didn't notice the music that much. I would therefore not classify it as particularly positive or negative at the moment after my first viewing.

Conclusion

Jurassic World - A New Age is in my eyes a successful finale, which offers a lot of variety. The big appearance of the old guard from JP1 is a feast for nostalgics, especially since all three of them have a supporting role in the film and are present throughout from beginning to end. But Owen Grady and Claire Dearing also continue to be the likable characters I've known and taken to heart since JW1. Maisie Lockwood is the most exciting character and offers potential for a new lead in future films, if there will be any. The action scenes are classy and variedly staged and it never gets boring. There are a lot of dinosaur species in the film, and there are also a lot of thrills and plenty of scary and thrilling moments that took my breath away. Suspense is guaranteed here, especially in the second half of the film. The CGI effects are great and the dinos look very good.

Overall, I am highly satisfied with the conclusion of the series and was able to leave with a satisfied grin. Even after a night of sleep I am still very convinced of the film and look forward to the second viewing.

9/10 points - High rewatch value.

I'm not going to pile on to the poor rating, because frankly, it's no worse than "Top Gun: Maverick" and that sad sack flick got accolades from the public. Most likely because they're afraid to tell their friends the movie is horrific. Same here. The dominos fall where they must.

Universal logo meant a few things post 1993. Dinosaurs and theme parks. They invested so much into this franchise, some would say they invented the tie-in theme ride. First to have a world renown trolley tour of their backlot. Universal meant "wonder" When you paired this up with Steven Spielberg, they could print money. That was the case with the first of this trilogy. "Jurassic World" made so much money, it was a no-brainer more were in the works. And more will most likely be made next.

I am exhausted thinking about that.

Because dinosaurs are lame. Cool for kids, I guess. But the nostalgia I had for "Jurassic Park" ended when I grew up and realized how lumbering and dumb dinosaurs were. I wasn't even all that young when THAT came out. Here we have the introduction of a world...yes...and actual Jurassic World where man and dinosaurs co-exist. A terrible concept to begin with. You spend the entire movie wondering how we function like this. It's bad enough watching stupid people who can't curb their dogs in the city. OR they could be put into service by gulping down homeless people. Ouch. Any way, some evil doer in the world has created a dino-locust? That which is controllable and put into service to destroy food supplies. For what reason? Who knows? BUT, kinda interesting IF you consider this man wants us all extinct. Or at least a large swath of the population. Hopefully it's people who can't tell the difference between a man and a woman. Kinda plays up here. Since dinosaurs, in this world, can procreate without a mate (like some lizards). Wait, are the powers that be admitting we are lizards? Perhaps. And, in the case of the movie, arguable that we deserve to be extinct. The villain, for those who care, is from "Jurassic Park" He is Dodgson. The smarmy guy who meets up with Wayne Knight's character in the first movie. Dude who had the shaving cream can.

Okay, there's that plot. But then there is Ellie and Alan's love story. I guess. They didn't have much chemistry back in 1993, they have zippo 2022. It is labored and tired. And though I'm sure Laura Dern is a nice person, she has lost a ton of her warmness. It reminds us the age of where they're at. And it's painful. To watch over middle-agers do stunts they clearly didn't perform is depressing. Meanwhile, the saving grace is Jeff Goldblum's off-the-cuff remarks that remind us what movie we're in. He is, as he was in 1993, the joy of the movie. His delivery of lines is pitch perfect, though winks at the audience. Since we wait for his next quip.

There's that plot. But then...Owen Grady and Claire. Now living like Doomsday preppers. They essentially kidnap a clone kid - Maisie - who we last saw in "Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom" (I walked out of that dreadful movie by the way). She feels suffocated by her living arrangement, as most kidnapped kids should feel. But under the guise of her safety.

So yeah, you get it...this movie is just too much movie attempting to cram into one movie. A series is better suited for so much fan service. And that sense of wonder is dead. Perhaps our society is too cynical to enjoy a mindless ride. It's hard to tell, since we are very far gone from Spielberg's point of view when it comes to sense of wonder. That died with "Schindler's List" and hasn't come back.

I will say this, IF you are having a bad day, or are stressed out and you want your brain to just tune out for a couple of hours. This tends to be the better choice then aforementioned "Top Gun: Maverick" It isn't a good movie, but it will give you a goose here and there when it comes to nostalgia. Director Colin Trevorrow is getting the brunt of Hollywood now. Having been booted from "Star Wars" to helm this may have re-wired his brain to play things safe. They can pay as much fan service as they want, one needs to be a fan to enjoy some of the easter eggs.

For me, I am dino-saured out.

If you are a fan of dinosaurs fighting each other, this movie is for you. If you are a fan of suspenseful moments where dinosaurs are hunting humans and the humans are trying to escape death, boy, you're in for a real treat. I was in awe by the action scenes in this movie and how realistic the graphics of the dinosaurs were. The last section of the movie is packed with dinosaur fighting scenes, you'll love it. There were a few notable scenes, especially the ones with the baby raptor dinosaur, where it looked TOO fake with too much CGI because it didn't blend well with the forest background. It didn't detract too much from the immersion of the movie but it was definitely noticeable.

The story was decent. It does a decent job of recapping the previous movie story a little bit. You will greatly benefit if you remember what happened in the earlier movies because they pretty much get into the story and continue it. The relationship between the characters will make much more sense if you remember what they did in the past. I didn't like how the movie just drops newly introduced characters. Especially in the first half, there are times where they introduce a new actor and then the story changes locations and you never see that actor again. They introduce dinosaurs that react to lazer pointers but you never see them again after that.

I'm not a big fan of the middle part since it drags on a little bit. The part where people are sneaking into the lab and there's heavy dialog wasn't presented interesting enough to me..

The acting is superb from all the actors. The way they acted terrified from these fake CGI dinosaurs were very believable. Jeff Goldblum was funny and talked eloquently as he always does. The audience at my movie theatre laughed at some of his dialog. I didn't see the other jurassic park movies from the 90's with the original actors. Jurassic World: Dominion - Spoiler free review.
rashid-573510 June 2022
Most of us who grew up with the original JP were captivated by the film in many different ways. Some people loved the grandeur of such creatures, some loved the thrill of a summer blockbuster done right and the rest loved both those aspects.

That movie has been loved by us for decades now, so I'm not going to compare the latest installment to it. That's unfair given the nature of the present day audience, who are kids just like we were but with way more pretentious ideologies and social media influenced interests.

(I myself avoided such a fate, given that social media in general started shaping the younger generation right after I took on more adult responsibilities in life)

Now, let's get into it.

Jurassic World: Dominion is by no means a bad movie.

Given what we went through in the last one(which isn't the directors fault, he did his job right), you would think that this doesn't deserve the hate it's getting.

However, the strangest thing about this movie is that whatever makes it worth watching is also the stuff that quickly ruins it.

If you're going to make a dinosaur movie, then make a dinosaur movie.

Instead what we get is an erratic attempt at merging this concept with those from the fast and furious/mission impossible movies and trying to force the same old pandering we've seen one too many times.

And like I mentioned, that's pretty much what makes this entertaining enough to sit through but also leaves you dissatisfied at the end of it.

We're here to watch Jurassic World, not the Avengers.

I will say that the film starts off very strong, and does make me care about the little girl from the last movie. Her storyline was surprisingly inspiring, and could have paved the way for a much better plot overall.

Past the halfway mark however, it quickly becomes a mess of rushed plot lines all trying to close off the story as a whole and you are left with a feeling of emptiness when the credits roll.

Another glaring issue was that whatever the trailer was advertising as the plot, is almost non existent in this movie. Even the scene of the T-rex "attacking" a movie theatre is simply for the online marketing.

There is hardly any real threat faced by the human race, which does make sense to be honest but it's not in keeping with what the last movie did right by setting up.

I was ready to hate this movie just for its diversion from the source material and the original trilogy. I instead dislike it for trying too hard to match up to said material, but without any sense of purpose or care.

The lines are cheesy, the acting is semi decent but not inspired, the dinosaurs are almost forgotten in a movie called Jurassic World that took two movies to setup, but are also pushed into every minute of screen-time.

It feels like a poorly constructed ride with characters that are written even worse and have the most cliché motivations.

All in all, I would suggest watching this movie at-least once on a big screen with a nice bag of popcorn to go with it. It will not be what you want, but is a good enough experience that you will not want to leave halfway.

The old cast appearing in the film didn't seem forced in my book, just a huge coincidence that they would all be together as the film went on.

There is no real way that they should meet(old and new cast), but they do!

That's just bad editing, which there seems to be a lot of during it's 2 hour 30 minute runtime. There was no reason for it to be this long, but it is.

I rate it 5/10.

If they ever make a new series of movies, I would like them to be their own thing, and an extension of the original trilogy as opposed to this weird attempt at showcasing the dangers of genetic power.

Best dinosaur movie in 20 years
korialfox7 June 2022
Jurassic World Dominion, unlike many other sequels in this saga, accomplishes what it set out to do. For casual viewers it has enough action, moments of wonder -that seemed to be missing in this franchise for the longest time- and enough plain fun. For the fans of the Jurassic movies it's a nostalgic joyride from start to finish.

Pros:

+ It's 6th movie in a franchise that manages not to feel dull and dumb.

+ Gone are the stupid moments of dinosaurs swallowing ringing cell phones, escape from dinosaur on high heels or dinosaurs smiling.

+ The plot, unlike in many of it's predecessors, actually makes more sense from scientific standpoint. It's still an action sci-fi horror monster movie, but it is consistent to the saga's mythos and characters.

+ Features more dinosaurs than all of the other movies combined, and the new ones are different and exciting.

+ The different locations of this movie from the previous tropical islands makes it stand out visually.

+ Fixes some of the plot holes of the saga, explains some character motivations and quickly resolves idiotic plotlines from the previous movie.

+ The script is very tight, I was amazed how they managed to fit everything into the runtime. Ending is not overdone like in the previous four movies and it is more impactful.

+ Stupid dialogue is pretty much gone, caricatures of human beings are not present. Some characters are fixed to be much better this time around. Some dialogue is surprisingly great. Fun jokes.

+ Some brilliant camerawork throughout, great effects, brilliant visuals.

+ The story weaves it's many protagonists through the plot and puts them all together for the grand finale in a believable way.

+ Great star power, the original cast elevates this movie and it's just a mystery to me why it took 29 years to put them in a movie together again.

+ Brains and fan moments throughout the movie that many of the sequels lacked.

Cons:

  • The movie has very little time to breathe, I would appreciate a 15 minute longer version with more character development and dialogue.


  • The cut suffers sometimes from the same issue as the last two movies, it is in some scenes way too abrupt.


  • When the score doesn't play John Williams themes, it's mostly only above average.


  • Missed opportunities for some side characters.


  • The opening montage to catch up on the plot of previous movies is poorly done. It throws so much information on you and serves very little purpose other than exposition. It starts out like a B movie.


I don't think anybody expected a genre defying experience like Jurassic Park brought in 1993. It definitely shows though that some of the ideas from the original are brought up here: Cloning, impact on humanity, mixing of species. While every other sequel after that mainly served to be a fun summer blockbuster, this movie surprised me in delving slightly back into these ideas from the original. Since then, there always was some dumb moment in each of the sequels that made me cringe: The entire San Diego sequence from the second movie, the terrible second half of the third movie, the stupidity of the fourth movie that among other things suggested dinosaurs have human-like IQ and the entire fifth movie, that seems mostly like a parody. Jurassic World Dominion is fun, almost entirely absent of these moments and has enough for you to enjoy it, especially if you are a fan of the original. 8/10.

Jurassic World Dominion Roars Back into Theaters
Stream2BigScreen_Movie_Reviews13 June 2022
Jurassic World: Dominion opened in theaters this weekend. It is the highly anticipated sixth installment in the Jurassic Park franchise. In Dominion, we find out whether the dinosaurs, who were released into the world at the end of Fallen Kingdom, have been integrated into the greater society and what effect their presence has on the broader ecosystem. It's been almost 30 years since we were first introduced to dinosaurs in modern times; but, six films later, are we still in awe of the scientific feats of DNA splicing and cloning? Here's whether going back to Jurassic World is worth all of that anticipation.

Jurassic World: Dominion brings back Owen Grady (Pratt) and Claire Dearing (Howard), who are raising the teenage clone, Maisie Lockwood (Sermon). They are protecting her from evil corporate interests who seek to capture and study her for their own nefarious reasons. Also, Elli Sattler (Dern) and Alan Grant (Neill) are back to investigate a potential ecological disaster brought on by genetically modified locusts rabidly devouring the world's crops. Then, there is Ian Malcolm (Goldblum) and Ramsay Cole (Athie) as fixtures of the corporation, Biosyn, which is at the center of all of these machinations. There's also a dynamic pilot, Kayla Watts (Wise), and a manipulative CEO of Biosyn, Lewis Dodgson (Scott). Oh man, did I forget anything? Um... prehistoric ravenous hijinks ensue.

Okay, as you can see, there is a lot going on in Jurassic World: Dominion. It's not necessarily complicated, but it is a lot to follow. These Jurassic Park movies always have a bit of an issue getting bogged down explaining the science of this all. In Dominion, they have to talk about genetic splicing and cloning and ecology, and it just goes on and on. Sattler and Grant are focused on stealing the DNA of these destructive locusts to prove that Biosyn is evil. Owen and Claire are focused on protecting Maisie from Biosyn. In a sense, it feels like so much is going on that there is not enough time for the characters to run and scream from the dinosaurs. That's the unfortunate part if you really like that aspect from the original.

Despite these reservations of the plot, the movie does have its exciting parts. There are dinosaur chases through the streets, through the jungle and through the Biosyn facilities. DeWanda Wise plays a tough-as-nails, wisecracking pilot, who seems to be the most competent of all of our characters. She gets good one-liners and has a magnetic personality. Her presence adds a lot of energy to what could become stale. I'll also note that the legacy characters of Sattler, Grant and Malcolm give exactly what you want. It's like no time has passed at all. The nostalgia is very high and they effectively scratch that Jurassic Park itch.

Ultimately, Jurassic World: Dominion is an enjoyable, escapist summer blockbuster. The problem here is that there is too much going on and it doesn't exactly all come together. There are probably too many characters that distract from the main attraction - the dinosaurs. Nevertheless, there are good dinosaur chases and exciting moments with a great new character played by DeWanda Wise. While I wouldn't call Jurassic World: Dominion essential, it certainly is good enough for a matinee viewing, so get your bowl of popcorn.

Jurassic World was a great reboot of the franchise ignited by Jurassic Park, the second film, Forbidden Kingdom, was alright, I heard negative things about the third in the trilogy, but I was prepared to see it and judge it for myself. Basically, four years after the volcanic eruption on Isla Nublar and the breakout of the dinosaurs at the Lockwood Estate incident who are freely roaming across the earth. Claire Dearing (Bryce Dallas Howard), former operations manager of Jurassic World, is still working for the Dinosaur Protection Group. She and former Jurassic World ethologist Owen Grady (Chris Pratt) are in a relationship and living in the Sierra Nevada mountains in a remote cabin, secretly raising teenage Maisie Lockwood (Isabella Sermon), Benjamin Lockwood's cloned granddaughter. One day, Blue, the Velociraptor that Owen trained, unexpectedly arrives at the cabin with an asexually reproduced offspring which Maisie names Beta. Biosyn Genetics, a rival company of InGen, is conducting research on dinosaurs genes, hoping for medical and agricultural breakthroughs to global issues. Biosyn wants to study Maisie's DNA for their research, Owen and Claire warn her not to go out. But Maisie is frustrated with living in seclusion, and has been sneaking away, and is soon spotted and kidnapped, along with Beta, by Biosyn operatives. Elsewhere, evolved giant locusts have appeared in huge swarms and are threatening the global food supply. Paleobotanist Dr. Ellie Sattler (Laura Dern) is suspicious that Biosyn created the locusts, observing that crops grown by the company have been left uneaten. Believing the locust's DNA dates to the Cretaceous period, Ellie approaches former partner and paleontologist Dr. Alan Grant (Sam Neill), who agrees to help investigate Biosyn. With assistance from CIA contacts, Claire and Owen track Maisie and Beta to Malta. There, dinosaurs are on the black market, and when the market is raided by authorities, dinosaurs are unintentionally released, causing havoc. Claire and Owen find out from a Biosyn employee that Maisie and Beta are being transported to Biosyn's secluded headquarters in the Dolomite Mountains in Italy. Former Air Force and cargo pilot Kayla Watts (DeWanda Wise) wants to help Owen and Claire and offers to fly them to facility. Meanwhile, Alan and Ellie have been invited to Biosyn by their friend, chaos theorist Dr. Ian Malcolm (Jeff Goldblum), now working with them, and they are introduced to Biosyn CEO Lewis Dodgson (Campbell Scott) (previously seen with Dennis Nedry in Jurassic Park). Ian is secretly working to uncover Dodgson's illegal activities, with communications director Ramsay Cole (Mamoudou Athie) aiding him. Lead geneticist Dr. Henry Wu (B. D. Wong), the scientist behind the dinosaur cloning programs at Jurassic Park and Jurassic World, genetically engineered the locusts and crops with Biosyn seed to dominate the agricultural market. Wu meets Maisie and explains that she is not a clone, she is in fact the asexually conceived daughter of Charlotte Lockwood (Isabella Sermon and Elva Trill). Charlotte died from a genetic disorder, but she had altered Maisie's DNA to make her immune. Wu believes that Maisie's and Beta's DNA are key to creating a pathogen to halt the locust outbreak. Approaching Biosyn, Kayla's cargo plane is attacked by a group of Quetzalcoatlus. Claire ejects while Owen and Kayla survive a crash landing. After encountering a Therizinosaurus and a Pyroraptor, the three regroup. Inside Biosyn, Ian gives Ellie an access card, she and Alan access a restricted lab where they steal a locust sample and find Maisie. Discovering the locust lab was breached, Dodgson destroys all evidence of the experiment by igniting the lab, inadvertently starting a fire that spreads to Biosyn's outer dinosaur valley. He also fires Ian for exposing his operation. After Alan, Ellie, and Maisie find Ian, they meet up with Owen, Claire, and Kayla. Meanwhile, Dodgson tries to escape with dinosaur embryos, but the power fails, he is trapped and subsequently killed by three Dilophosaurus. Electronic implants summon the dinosaurs to the Biosyn headquarters to protect them from the fire, while Owen rescues Beta. A Giganotosaurus terrorises the group until the Therizinosaurus and the Tyrannosaurus Rex kill it. The group escapes in a helicopter, taking Wu with them. Once back on the mainland, Wu successfully neutralises the locusts by releasing one carrying a pathogen he discovered. After joining Ian and Ramsay in testifying against Biosyn, Ellie and Alan rekindle their relationship. Owen, Claire, and Maisie return home and reunite Beta and Blue. Around the world, dinosaurs adapt to co-existing with modern animals while Biosyn Valley is declared a dinosaur sanctuary by the United Nations. Also starring Omar Sy as Barry Sembène, Justice Smith as Franklin Webb, Daniella Pineda as Dr. Zia Rodriguez, Scott Haze as Rainn Delacourt, and Dichen Lachman as Soyona Santos. It is good to bring together Dern, Neill and Goldblum from the Jurassic Park trilogy, and Pratt and Dallas Howard from the Jurassic World trilogy, all give performances as good as you'd expect, but as before, the dinosaurs more often steal the show. What made the original Jurassic Park great was the sense of wonder with fantastic CGI bringing dinosaurs to life, the first Jurassic World did recapture some of the magic, but as with the second instalment of this trilogy, the story and writing is hardly prioritised. The plot is almost non-sensical, the globe-trotting element is slightly pointless, and although some of the chases and thrills do get your attention, it feels predictable and obviously style over substance, but it's not a terrible science-fiction action. Okay!

Great Fun!
Pairic13 June 2022
Jurassic World Dominion: Dinosaurs everywhere, yeah they spread out after the escapes in the last film. Of course there's a black market, trading in the creatures. In some places there's a modus vivendi, wonderful to watch brontosauri proceeding stately, respected by loggers. But other outfits illegally trap, breed and export the dinosaurs. Clair Dearing is back combating these trappers, Owen Grady (on horseback) rounds up the animals to be transported to reserves. They both live in a remote cabin in the Sierra Nevada mountains with the cloned Maisie Lockwood. But Maisie is kidnapped along with the baby raptor Beta. A parallel story-line involves Ellie Sattler and Alan Grant trying to solve the riddle of what has caused a plague of giant locusts which is devouring crops and causing famine. They link up with Ian Malcolm. There's also the sinister BioSyn company which runs a dinosaur reserve in a temperate rain forest in the the Dolomite Mountains. The two narratives eventually merge in that valley.

Great scenes of battling dinosaurs but also TV News shows about the problems the creatures cause. Small flying dinosaurs devouring doves released at a wedding, a trawler being dragged under by a sea dinosaur. Planes are brought down by flocks of Quetzalcoatlus and a Giganotosaurus combats a T-Rex. The screenplay won't win an Oscar but there are frightening, amusing and thrilling scenes. Also some excellent scenes of raptors pursuing motorbikes and and chasing people across rooftops. My favourite scene was an escooter rider being plucked up and devoured! A chase movie, an action thriller and a conspiracy involving a Bond style villain. Just enjoy it! Directed by Colin Trevorrow, written by Trevorrow and Emily Carmichael. 7/10.

Fan service and homage
Movi3DO15 June 2022
How many T. Rex getting hurt does it take to stop this franchise?

The conclusion to the Jurassic World trilogy. The movie itself is not really about the plot. Instead, it's an amalgamation of references to past movies and fan-service moments, and I had a fun time.

If you rewatch the previous 5 movies leading up to this one, the callbacks would be so in-the-face. Multiple quotes, objects, and characters made me do that Leonardo DiCaprio pointing meme. They were littered everywhere throughout the runtime. Even the ways some of the characters died in this movie were copies from previous ones. Not gonna lie it's pretty satisfying recognizing those references.

Even though Dominion doesn't offer fan-service to the level of Endgame or No Way Home, there were still a lot. Not all of them worked though, as some felt kinda cringe.

However, this doesn't discredit the solid sequences of actions in the movie. Once they forced the setup of the plot, the movie turned into constant chasing and dinosaur attacks. The sequences were handled well and created high levels of intensity. The jump scares didn't feel cheap or predictable, heightening the intensity furthermore.

I have mentioned many of the problems of this movie. The plot was basic to the bone. It's just there so we can have a proper movie. The villain character was the typical forgettable evil villain. The dialogues were corny, and sadly even the veteran cast members could not save those lines.

Overall, if you come in expecting a thrilling adventure with lots of service and homage, you will have a blast. 7-7.5/10.

This review is coming from someone who grew up with this franchise and one that means a lot to me. I even think Jurassic World is an okay film and Fallen Kingdom, well that was the only Jurassic film I did not like. Knowing Sam Neill, Laura Dern and Jeff Goldblum we're gonna return is what really got my hyped for the film. I went into this film not expecting much and kept an open mind despite the critic reviews, but what I got was a very over complicated plot when it didn't need to be that led to a very underwhelming and anti climactic conclusion. The movie puts too much emphasis on this bug sub plot that just over complicates the whole story and tries to take it too seriously when Jurassic Park is supposed to be fun and exciting. Now the weakest part of this movie is definitely Campbell Scott's character, the villain of the story. He just comes across as so silly and cartoonish and every time he was on screen, it took me out of the movie. I will never be able to understand anybody who tells me they can deal watching a character like him on screen because I despise that character and his sub plot so much to the point where it ruined the entire movie for me. I definitely enjoyed seeing the OG characters back and it really did bring a smile to my face when we see them again, but certain things didn't feel right like Alan and Ellie's getting back together romance. It felt so forced, rushed and unnatural and this is coming from someone who loves seeing these two as a couple in the first movie and didn't understand why they broke up in the third. The movie also turns into a random spy espionage in the middle of the movie which felt very out of place for a Jurassic film. Once again, these new Jurassic films are replaced with more CGI dinosaurs rather than animatronics and I've gotten pretty much used to it at the point, but then again I miss the times when I would look at the Dinos and think to myself wow that actually looks real or that actually looks terrifying, but sadly I get none of that in these Jurassic world films.

Overall I really loved seeing the OG characters again despite them being a little under utilized and almost served no purpose other than fan service. My main gripe of the film is definitely the script with Campbell Scott and his bug plot when this movie is supposed to be about dinosaurs. If I had to pick one bad finale of a trilogy, I would pick Rise of Skywalker over Jurassic World Dominion.

Usually I'm pretty detailed with my reviews but I'm going to try and keep my review of this mess short and not so sweet.

Once again directed by Colin Trevorrow, whom has done all the Jurassic World movies, this latest Jurassic World continues this trilogies goal of overcomplicating the once simple premise of Jurassic Park.

I'll try to avoid spoilers but this plot is set four years after Fallen Kingdom. Dinosaurs are now living amongst the humans but two threats are not only endangering them but mankind. A locust is now spreading to the crops on earth and a bioengineering company that is creating them.

Let's face it, everyone who saw the trailer are only seeing it because it involves the casts from both eras of the franchise, which is indeed cool but Trevorrow clearly didn't care about that when he wrote and directed this mess, because if he did, he would have come up with a more suitable plot than this. The original was simple and to the point, while this takes the scientific element way too far.

The performances are as good as you expect but everything else is an undeniable disaster, from the overly green screened environments and CGI dinosaurs that have somehow only gotten worse with each film. Seriously, how is it that the 1993 film that inadvertently started it all looks better.

So overall, in short, watch the first film. Heck, I'd watch the second and third film over this. There's trying too hard and then there's not trying at all, this is definitely the latter.

Third Best Of The Six: An Honest Review

I am a huge JP/JW fan, and I WANTED to LOVE this film, but I'm going to put together an honest review here.

First, the pros: The plot line is a logical continuation and doesn't feel forced. The way the JP and JW cast get meshed together works very well, in my opinion. The movie has some very exciting and suspenseful moments....more than I've seen out of a JP/JW movie since Lost World!!

Now, the cons: It is a slow moving film, and the VAST majority of the exciting and suspenseful moments occur in a 30 minute window near the end of the film. I wish there was more. There are definitely some great action sequences at the start and middle of the film, and they are FUN, but they are predictable and, therefore, don't build suspense. My final criticism is on the CGI. Honestly, there were some sequences where the CGI did NOT look fluid, but rather looked choppy and lower quality than anything since the original JP. It almost felt like their CGI budget was cut or something. The most exciting sequences, the CGI was spot on, but in other sequences, it was just WEIRD to watch.

All in all, I give this film 8 stars since the plot was logical/believable, the acting was good (VERY good acting by the original JP cast), and the end of the movie saved the day by bringing in some REAL suspense.

I didn't enjoy Jurassic World Fallen Kingdom and it was a sign that this franchise had run it's course. Dominion is the final nail in the coffin in what I'd hoped would be a fun film with plenty of dinosaur action, a sense of danger and adventure and a few callbacks to the first film seeing as the original cast were brought back.

Well the film delivers on very little of that, the plot is not only ridiculous but it's also very boring and never takes off. I'm just expecting a film on par with Jurassic Park here, it's never going to happen but in an attempt to try and bring something new to the franchise Dominion has lost all sense of why I've enjoyed most of the sequels.

It reminds me a bit of Star Wars The Last Jedi, a film that wanted to be so radically different from any other Star Wars film that it lost sight of what I enjoy about these films. Also same with Shane Black's The Predator from 2018, stop trying to drastically change the formula so much to the point where we're paying to see a film that's not how it's been marketed as at all.

When you watch a Jurassic film you want a sense of dread and danger as we wonder who will meet a cruel fate next to one of the dinosaurs and who will survive and escape. I don't want boring subplots about a kidnapped girl who is a clone of some character that we see for the first time in this film. It's a waste of time in a film that's already overlong and overstuffed with filler. Without sounding old and cynical I miss the days of the briskly paced Lost World and Jurassic Park 3. Heck Dominion doesn't even feel like a conclusive chapter or has any sense of finality to the 6 films.

I'd say don't waste your time and money, if you want to watch a Jurassic film you're better off just watching any of the other films (except maybe Fallen Kingdom) or watching Prehistoric Planet if you want a dinosaur fix. What Walts Watching
waltermwilliams13 June 2022
This could have been Universals Jurassic answer to Marvels Endgame, but it's not!

Sure all the characters who survived the original movies are back for this 6th instalment and that's a good thing, which could have been even better if they'd shared more screen time together.

It was great to see Sam Neil, Lauren Dern and Jeff Goldblum back in action alongside Chris Pratt & Bryce Dallas Howard on the Big Screen with amazing sound.

Campbell Scott's head of Biosyn, "Lewis Dodgson" seems to be modelled on Apples Founder Steve Jobs.

"Archive 81's" Mamoudou Athie is great as Ramsay Cole as is DeWanda Wise as the mercenary pilot, "Kayla Watts".

However one of this movies major issues is the amount of time it takes to spin out this hopefully final yarn from Director Colin Treverrow.

Its runtime is at least 30 minutes too long.

Fun Fact: there are more animatronics than any previous Jurassic or Lost World film in this very successful franchise.

It doesn't always work though because in the subterranean cave scene it plays out like the popular arcade game "Whack A Mole" it's that clunky and mechanical.

In fact, it looks like 1960's animation and I'm expecting Raquel Welch to jump out in a bear skin.

Don't get me wrong there are some cool creatures created for this movie that we've never seen before including something from a Thanks Giving Day Nightmare and the CGI is flawless and genuinely terrifying.

You will believe Dinosaurs exist.

But why are movie characters so dumb?

One moment they are saying "don't move" then they are racing around like ants, or another character creates a diversion while others look on instead of escaping.

None of them deserved to live through this fiasco and fly away safe in the Corporate Chopper.

Plus it feels like quite a few scenes we have seen before in this series...including trapped in upturned vehicles, seeking refuge in old outposts, another high tech centre for illegal DNA testing (think Isla Nublar etc), tourism options and much more. It becomes very formulaic.

There are some fun references for fans who've watched every movie that will make you cheer though.

This movie could have blown our minds with the set up from the previous release with closing Easter eggs of dinosaurs hunting surfers, but it barely touched on the real world problems of Dino's unleashed in the modern world.

Apart from the plot line of giant insects destroying crops and all that entails with end of the world philosophy.

Unfortunately insects are rarely as sexy as anything ending in saurs...they even admit that in their own dialogue.

If we are actually only 3 meals away from anarchy then maybe this was one movie too many that didn't deliver on the promise and I was so looking forward to that movie they teased us with in the trailers.

The ending is just downright laughable and corny.

Instead we get a Disney version of life finding a way thanks to Amblin and Universal.

Nostalgic Rollercoaster Ride
schoenbergermatthew12 June 2022
Jurassic Park was my childhood. When the movie came out in theaters, I was only 1 years old. I remember owning Jurassic Park years later on vhs, and it becoming one of my most prized possessions. The story, characters, pacing, special effects, and music are pitch perfect. When the Lost World: Jurassic Park came out, I was 5 years old, and I did not see it in theaters either. While it was a flawed sequel, I enjoyed watching it on vhs. The music, set pieces, and the inclusion of more dinosaurs made it a fun addition to the series. Jurassic Park III was the first film in the franchise that I actually saw in theaters in 2001. I remember loving it when I was 9 years old, but now it is my least favorite of the sequels. The runtime is too short, and I'm not just referring to humans running away from dinosaurs. The dialogue and characters and poorly written, and the quality of the cgi was downgraded. With that being said, the animatronic work still mostly holds up, except the Spinosaurus. Fast forward 14 and 17 years later, and I finally saw both Jurassic World and Jurassic World Fallen Kingdom in theaters. The experience of seeing the park finally open in Jurassic World was such an en incredible feeling. It was the closest to capturing the magic of the original Jurassic Park. Jurassic World Fallen Kingdom, like Jurassic Park III, tends to get better when repeat watches, but it is a lesser sequel in almost every way. This brings me to Jurassic World Dominion. While the film does have tonal issues and missteps, seeing the original trio together is worth the price of admission alone. While I think the current reviews are a bit harsh, the film is flawed. I would summarize the biggest issue as missed opportunities for the characters and story. The movie wraps up all six films in an interesting enough way, but doesn't completely satisfy or answer every question that you may have. Visually, the movie is gorgeous, and it has the most animatronics of any film in the franchise, with the cgi mixing well with the practical effects. Overall, Jurassic World Dominion is a nostalgic rollercoaster ride that thrilled me, slightly disappointed me, but never bored me.

This movie, like every other sequel in the franchise is not a perfect film. In Jurassic World Dominion, there are many things that deserve praise. The story and its ending, visual and sound effects, direction, performance of Goldblum, action scenes, and emotional weight all deserve praise.

But does this mean that the movie does not have flaws? Of course not. Jurassic World Dominion has several flaws that can be easily noticed if the person focuses well in it. Third, the person who is watching the movie can feel that there is neither an upgrade nor a downgrade if we want to compare Jurassic World Dominion to the previous installments. It would have been better if they worked on at least one upgrade.

But do all these flaws mean that I did not like Jurassic World Dominion? Of course not. On the contrary, I liked it so much and the way it ended the story that started with Jurassic Park 1993. When it comes to the score, I give Jurassic World Dominion 8 out of 10.

Four years after Isla Nublar was destroyed, dinosaurs now live-and hunt-alongside humans all over the world. This fragile balance will reshape the future and determine, once and for all, whether human beings are to remain the apex predators on a planet they now share with history's most fearsome creatures.

The movie is driven by action and visual effects, with little care given to things like character development or a well-written plot. The pace is fast, and the movie is exciting, but it's forgettable. The dialogue is often cheesy, and the acting is just okay with Sam Neill, Jeff Goldblum, and Chris Pratt phoning it in. There are a few themes that pop up such as the dangers of messing with nature, but they are quickly abandoned in favour of more action.

Amazing for what it is
wwtrd-3496414 June 2022
This is the first real Jurassic Park (World) movie in ages. Far superior to Jurassic Park 3 in every way, and completely better than anything the Jurassic World franchise has produced yet. Not only does it bring back the original crew, but this movie is clever, fun, scary and exciting. If I had to choose one thing to dislike about this movie, it would only be that it's a hyper simplistic plot. But that's not the point of the film. The purpose of this movie is to wrap up the Jurassic World and Park franchise, and it does it perfectly. Yes, the story itself isn't anything too impressive, but it's about as simplistic and complex as the original Jurassic Park, which is what you want in a dinosaur movie. It's not about some evil hybrid serial killer dinosaur, or some weird special agent hybrid dinosaur; it's a bit like a heist film with plenty of dinosaurs all throughout. The CGI is amazing, the acting is great, and the variety of creature is immense. But the best two things about this movie are the themes and stunning cinematography. The action scenes are jam packed with motion and power, without being overwhelming, and the dinosaurs are stunning and beautiful. Most scenes incorporating them are immaculate, visual, artistic, and inspiring. Best of all this movie has humor and horror. The funny bits are not the stupid slap stick childish jokes of the last three movies. These little humourous cues are organic and fun, mostly made by Ian Malcolm, which fits his character. No more mind numbing half winded jokes that are just randomly placed in the movie for a cheap laugh. That being said, the horror aspect of the movie was intense. Plenty of scary scenes to keep you on your toes; big vicious frightening dinosaurs, and gruesome death scenes akin to the first and second Park (Not World) movies. Just enough violence, just enough horror, and just enough joy. There are also plenty of call backs to the earlier films, and some retconning which helps bring certain character development points together. All in all, it was an amazing movie and worthy of it's title. GO SEE IT.

An Underwhelming Conclusion to the Jurassic World Trilogy
jaredkjacoby18 June 2022
Set four years after the events of Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom, Dominion has Owen and Claire raising Maisie alone in a remote area where she will not come into contact with anyone. However, employees from a dinosaur research company known as Biosyn Genetics kidnaps Maisie when she tries to leave as well as Blue's mysterious child. Claire and Owen set out to rescue them both. Meanwhile, Alan Grant and Ellie Sattler go to Biosyn to investigate the seeds that are left uneaten after a locust raid threatens food supply around the world.

As someone whose favorite movie is Jurassic Park, I am rather mixed in Jurassic World. It was fine, but it did not have the tension or thrill of the first film. I thought Fallen Kingdom was much better, but I am in the minority there. I thought it did a great job focusing on the fright of the dinosaurs as well as showing how humans can be just monstrous if not more so. I also thought the ending was a nice setup to this film and it made me pretty excited for the ending to this trilogy. Does it end with a bang or a whimper?

Let us start with the good. First of all, the cast is great. Seeing Sam Neill as Alan Grant and Lauren Dern as Ellie Sattler was a joy and they have just as smooth chemistry as they did nearly three decades ago. Some things never change with them, especially for Grant. Jeff Goldblum is much older, but he is as smooth and solid as ever as Ian Malcolm.

The World cast are no slouches either. Bryce Dallas Howard continues to improve as Claire as she grows from being a rather cowardly Jurassic World employee to a strong person who is not afraid to step into action. They even show how much she has grown from the first by having her go on a dangerous rescue mission in her first scene. Chris Pratt is great as Owen. I always felt that this has always been Pratt's coolest role where he is a bit more serious but he still has a sense of humor for the more insane encounters he and Claire face. Isabella Sermon is solid as the rebellious Maisie her backstory continues to be pretty fascinating. Of the new characters, I liked DeWanda Wise as Kayla Watts. She is a fun character to watch as she is skilled and energetic. Wise seems to have a blast in this role. The cast is great overall.

The cinematography is great. The shots look stunning as ever with some images that look almost out of a horror flick. The scene where Claire is trying to stay calm when encountering a carnivorous dinosaur showcases the movie's visual style perfectly. The dinosaurs look solid enough, though there are some scenes of questionable CGI. The action scenes are fun to watch overall, with the motorcycle chase standing out. The musical score by Michael Giacchino is fantastic and the sound design for the dinosaurs make them even more threatening. This all makes the movie technically solid. With a great cast, solid action, beautiful cinematography and some memorable new characters, why did I still leave the theater underwhelmed?

Jurassic World: Dominion is a movie that I wish that I loved, but I don't. In fact, it is pretty disappointing. First of all, the story is a jumbled mess. There is so much going on that it is hard to keep track with the plot. Even then, it starts off so slow that it gets difficult to invest in the story, but it does pick up a little bit around the beginning of the second act. As much as I love seeing Grand and Sattler again, their role feels more like having them for the sake of having them rather than truly needing them. Blue gets absolutely nothing to do, though if you thought she got too much screen time in the second film, you might appreciate this.

The biggest problem I have with the story though is the fact that it does little build upon the setup from the last film. Dinosaurs running around the real world? That sounds insane! There are so many ideas you can create with this premise, but most of the movie is about taking down another evil corporation and destroying the locusts. Locusts? I came to see this movie to see humanity live among dinosaurs. The locusts are unnecessary and they hinder the story more than anything. The one scene taking place underground where we get to see how dinosaurs are used in a club is more interesting than anything to do with locusts. Why could they not just build on that or other areas affected by the spread of the dinosaur population? That would have made for some great world-building.

As for the villains, they are disappointing as well. The main human villain, Lewis Dodgson has one threatening scene, but he is not given much to do after that. I thought the human from Fallen Kingdom was better because he was much more detestable and vile. That was the kind of villain that I wanted to punch. Dodgson is pretty evil too, but he feels more generic. As for the Giganotosaurus, it is a massive disappointment. It hardly acts like a threat to the main characters, yet it is treated like a villain. I think they did not give this dinosaur enough screen time. If they focused on this dinosaur more than the locusts, maybe they would have shown how much of threatening predator this beast could have been.

Despite my rant about the story and villains, I do not dislike Jurassic World: Dominion. I liked too much stuff in it to call it a bad film. I just wish it was great. It should have been great. That is why I feel so disappointed and underwhelmed with it. However, what does work works really well. If you are looking for a nostalgic experience and/or you want to see some cool dinosaur action, you'll get plenty of that here. Maybe it is time to lay this series to rest and move on before it can get really bad.

Warning: Spoilers
2 out of 7 found this helpful. Was this review helpful? Sign in to vote.
Permalink
The flaws in Jurassic World Dominion can be traced back to Jurassic World and especially Jurassic World Fallen Kingdom.

Jurassic World was somewhat of a remake of Jurassic Park. The difference was a fully operational park and a hybrid dinosaur. And it was just less good than the original. But still a very enjoyable movie in it's own right. Storywise it didn't do much to lead up to the events in Jurassic World Dominion though. This is where the problems started but the real problem is it's sequel.

Jurassic World Fallen Kingdom was just a mediocre movie. I loved the opening scene and the Gothic horror scenes in Lockwood Manor but the rest of the movie was pretty much subpar and very shallow. Storywise it didn't do anything for the franchise at all. It was just so empty. The movie didn't do anything to lead up to the events in Jurassic World Dominion, except let the dino's escape.

When watching Jurassic World Dominion I felt the movie suffered from the empty story Jurassic World Fallen Kingdom provided us with. It felt like the movie wanted to make up for this. Because of this, the plot felt shallow at times and many events and characters just dropped out of thin air without getting any kind of lead up story in the previous movies. Too many stories and characters are in this movie without an explanation. Did they have a choice though? No. There wasn't a good story to work with so they had to create the entire story for the last movie.

Colin Trevorrow said he always knew where he wanted to go, he knew the end. The problem is Jurassic World and (especially) Jurassic World Fallen Kingdom basically didn't do anything to lead up to that. Jurassic World Dominion did provide us with stories but there wasn't enough time to develop them because they were already coming to an end. Before you create an end, you have to work on a story and before Dominion, that basically didn't happen.

Why did I end up liking the movie anyway despite it's flaws?

I was smiling the entire time because I really enjoyed what I saw. It was a very enjoyable story and it was never boring. It felt like an homage to Jurassic Park and The Lost World Jurassic Park the entire time.

The action scenes are really great. That raptor chase is one of the best action scenes I've ever seen.

Whenever a dinosaur comes on to the screen it's just stunningly beautiful. Gorgeous scenes. And gorgeous landscapes to add to that.

The original cast together makes for beautiful and nostalgic scenes. It felt to me they stepped right back into their roles.

DeWanda Wise was a joy to watch. As far as new characters, hers got the right attention.

What are the negatives besides the flaws in the plot/story?

The soundtrack should have been better.

The finale wasn't bad but it was too weak.

Queen Rexy didn't get enough moments to shine in the movie.

There were several stupid moments and that doesn't do Jurassic Park and The Lost World Jurassic Park any justice. For example, when an Allosaurus and Carnotaurus are let loose, everybody just keeps looking at two people fighting instead of running for their life, far away from two very deadly predators.

I love Chris Pratt but how did a dinosaur not bite off Owen's hand yet?

At times it felt like the movie focused on locusts more than on dinosaurs.

There were very few dinosaur vs real world interactions. In the second half of the movie they basically returned to a park again.

Sometimes it felt they forgot what dinosaurs are. I know they don't want to depict them as monsters only but there is a certain limit as to how far you can push that I think. The carnivores were formidable predators and sometimes people get away with too much in the movie.

In the end it feels like a lot of potential was wasted in the Jurassic World trilogy, not just in Dominion. In Dominion they really try to make up for it but they ran out of time to do it without flaws. I am able to put the movie into that perspective that's why I do really like it.

Look, I'm a huge Jurassic Park fan. I love the original. I love The Lost World Jurassic Park. Jurassic World Dominion isn't Jurassic Park. It isn't The Lost World Jurassic Park. It just doesn't reach the quality of either of those movies. But in the end it's a highly enjoyable dinosaur movie that pays tribute to Spielberg's masterpieces. It's a great movie in it's own right.

I get all the disappointed reviews very well. I really do. I went to the cinema without any kind of expectation at all. In the end I felt it was the best movie in the Jurassic World trilogy.

3/10

Just got back from a friday early afternoon show. My feelings about this are pretty fresh and may mellow over the coming weeks, but I was not impressed.

This is essentially The Rise of Skywalker for the JP franchise. Lots of fan service, lots of Spielberg references, lots of "remember that from the previous films??!" moments. It lacked any compelling story, making a Monsanto-type corporation the antagonist/bad guy with heroes/protagonists that make nonsensical decisions that serve only to propel the audience to the next action sequence.

I can't tell if this movie needed to be split into two films so each could breathe on their own and develop its own story, or if this script just needed several more rewrites to get to a better form. At 2h30m, its a bloated frenzied mess that has huge holes in the plot, massive leaps of logic, and no real sense of what it wanted to say.

The first JP was a marvel. Groundbreaking visual effects, one of the most memorable scores of the last 30 years, timeless quotes and sequences that entertain my kids as much as it entertained me when I first saw it. And no real heavey plot driven story. It was pure escapism. Jurassic World: Dominion is the sort of Frankenstein's monster it is trying to warn the world about. These hybrid dinosaurs, these man-made attempts to recapture the natural elegance of something less engineered, are to be feared as well as the people that seek the power to make and control them. The same could be said for the current decisionmakers that greenlit this to the theaters. Lots of recycled parts from other better movies to produce something loud, brash and just unintelligible.

Don't let my 5 star rating lead you to think this is well made movie.. it is NOT. But the joy of seeing Sattler, Grant and Malcolm together on screen again did make me a little sentimental and the dinosaurs look better than ever and will never fail to entertain me.

The other characters are quite dull however, and the plot is horrible.

It's just all over the place and full of tired clichés, starting right from the beginning with Maisie being a rebellious teenager who is mad at Owen and Claire for wanting to protect her from evil kidnappers. She's the clone of a brilliant scientist, a genius, but she definitely doesn't act like it. The whole dynamic between her and her new parents is very unbelievable and doesn't feel natural at all, despite the good acting of Bryce Dallas Howard, who now has to portray a totally different personality compared to JW 1.

Owen is boring and stereotypical as ever, his only value is his magical ability to control not just the raptors he raised with the palm of his hand, but also communicate/understand every other dinosaur. I liked the continued close bond with blue and her baby (yes I know they just want to sell cute baby dinosaurs but I'm easy like that, I love a cute baby dinosaurs. Hope Blue&baby make it into a LEGO Jurassic World spinoff, so my son can enjoy them too!).

The new character, pilot/ dino smuggler Kayla, is just as cliché and boring as Owen: the typical tough badass with a good heart and a sentimental relationship with their vehicle of choice. I swear I've seen this a hundred times and they never get any more believable.

Same with the stylish villain Santos, along with the whole Malta/ black market setting and plotline. All of it, except for the dinosaurs, could have been part of any other action movie, like Bond or Bourne. It was still cool to watch, despite the raptor hybrids being very inconsistent in their abilities: they are as fast as cars and motorcycles, but slower than Claire. Okay.

The original Jurassic Park cast members are completely fine and charming as ever, it's a shame they didn't really get the chance to shine in their very underwhelming plot line, which often feels like a lifeless copy of the original trilogy and less like the hommage it was probably intended to be.

The main reason is the absurdly incompetent main villain, Dodgeson. None of the main characters ever has to be especially intelligent or even lucky, because he doesn't give them a challenge.

When we first arrive at the Biosyn facility, it looks quite impressive, like Sattler and Grant will have to navigate stealthily among a brainwashed cult of opportunistic scientists. But no, they are more or less immediately handed everything they need to get to the evidence they came for. We are supposed to believe that surveillance is so tight that they can't talk openly anywhere with Cole or Malcolm, but as soon as they have their keycard they can go wherever they want and suddenly no one is watching them?

Also Dodgeson has this highly skilled expensive kidnapping team but as soon as the girl is inside the lab she can just press a button and leave without anyone stopping here?

Biosyn captures and contains dinosaurs like Giganotosaurus but they don't manage to keep a bunch of burning locusts safe in an underground lab?

Hard to believe that an idiot like Dodgeson would have made it so far. His confrontation of Cole and his attempt to escape seem like they were written by a child.

And don't get me started on Henry Wu, who now has longer hair and a completely new personality. He's remorseful and kindhearted and in the end it's him who saves the world from the locusts (more or less off screen too), not any of our supposedly smart and courageous heros.

But the worst thing about this movie isn't even the stupid plot, it's the complete lack of magic. In a way the new trilogy mirrors the old one, which started great but got steadily worse.

I rate the other movies as follows: JP1: 9/10, JP2: 8/10, JP3: 6/10. JW1:8/10, JW2: 7/10.

Keep in mind I always add extra stars for the dinosaurs alone, because I just freaking love them so much.

This was the worst Jurassic movie of all, and it's a shame. Seeing all the main characters united for the first time should have been a great moment, but it was just so underwhelming and their interactions between the two generations was a boring waste of potential.

Personally I would have brought back Ian Malcolm's daughter in a slightly less annoying adult version and also given Blue a bigger role instead of adding new characters with lame backstories that led nowhere (Kayla and Denise for example).

Also Maisie should definitely have been given something meaningful to contribute besides her DNA.

All in all, the movie is pretty to look at (not in 3D though) but overall disappointing.

I would have loved for the series to go out with a (big) bang.

Jurassic World 3 - A very, very average sequel that plays it safe
Hey_Harry11 June 2022
"Jurassic World Dominion" is the third and (hopefully) the last entry in the Jurassic World trilogy. It's safe to say the franchise has run out of steam at this point and arguably, it's been the case with all Jurassic Park/Jurassic World sequels since "The Lost World." At the very least, I anticipated that "Dominion" would surpass the mediocrity of "Fallen Kingdom" but somehow, "Dominion" wound up being even more convoluted and messy than Fallen Kingdom.

To sum it up, Dominion many problems including a rushed script, too many subplots, disposable characters and a very bland, forgettable villain. One of the movie's biggest draws was returning characters from the first "Jurassic Park", Alan Grant, Ellie Sattler and Ian Malcolm, but even the reunion of the original cast members doesn't save "Dominion" from being an incredibly bland entry in the JW franchise, although admittedly I was happy to see Jeff Goldblum receive more screentime where he gets to deliver some genuinely funny lines. Unfortunately, the same cannot be said about the rest of the characters who feel underdeveloped and underused throughout the film despite a few moments where the character dynamic between the old and new characters was actually decent. If only the script was better then "Dominion" could've done a better job of bridging together the two franchises, Jurassic Park and Jurassic World" and its characters and brought a satisfying close to the series.

Overall, "Jurassic Park Dominion" is a sequel that plays it safe by relying on fan service and even toning down the violence in an effort to make the film more family-friendly than its predecessors as there's hardly much blood spilled in the movie. Granted, Jurassic Park/World has always been a PG-13 franchise that doesn't rely heavily on gore although the franchise still didn't shy away from depicting gruesome dinosaur kills. In spite of the above, Dominion, which features dinosaurs roaming around on a global scale, somehow manages to be even more tame than the previous JP/JW films where it contains fewer dinosaur kills and violence. All of the above contribute to "Dominion" being a very average, by-the-numbers sequel and a good indicator that the dino franchise has completely run out of steam at this point and probably should remain extinct.
