In my opinion, the mistake lies in having to compare the last film of the saga with the first and unattainable Jurassic Park, and compare Treworrow to Spielberg

"Jurassic World Dominion" is not a great movie, nor something that will go down in history like Jurassic Park. It is not a particularly bold or in-depth film in the themes, although we were pleased to see several animatronics as well as the CGI

It remains a good adventure film, in line with the other Jurassic World, even if in my humble opinion, the chorality of the two parallel stories is successful and certainly the old "magical trio" brings something more to the film than the two previous films

It is not a hair-pulling film, but certainly a good film, with excellent rhythm, good narrative arc and nostalgic at the right point, without forcibly leveraging the past and giving everyone functional roles to the story

Although the main role is entrusted to the new characters, it would be wrong to say that the old ones have been reinserted just for "fanservice", their story is still dealt with in a worthy way and well interpreted

Beyond some scientific forcings, however present throughout the franchise which, however, does not want to represent the pure dinosaurs but admittedly allows some legitimate licenses, the film is of a good standard, and indeed has the merit of including other different species of dinosaurs, with scientific accuracy, demonstrating how scientific knowledge has evolved

The film turned out to be pleasant and I give it, on a scale of 1 out of 10, a good 7, like the first Jurassic World, to which a nice + must be added, thanks to the presence of the performer Jeff Goldblum, the exceptional Laura Dern and the stainless Sam Neill

So the film is more than good for me, I place it only behind the first two of Spielberg and a little above the first Jurassic World

I do not agree with the reviews that even, at the moment, give it to the last place of the new trilogy (even if it is still early)

Something revolutionary or equal to the first film could not be expected

So it deserves to be seen without the sometimes stereotyped prejudices, of some criticism.

Even though this movie has an amazing cast consisting of a few legacy characters and, in my opinion, beautifully done visual effects, this movie did not feel very Jurassic for at least 60% of the movie, and that's saying something. Laura Dern, Sam Neill, and Jeff Goldblum all return from the original Jurassic Park to help take down Biosyn Genetics, who have begun to engineer giant crop-eating locusts to take control of the world's food supply. And while I enjoy getting more insight on InGen's biggest corporate rival, the overall effect it had at the end of the movie didn't really pay off. We didn't see many dinosaurs in this movie compared to the amount of them we saw in previous films, and that really disappointed me considering this movie is literally called "JURASSIC World". And while the scenes in Malta and the last 20 minutes were action packed and thrilling, it would've been better to see more dinosaurs interact with the main cast throughout the movie. But WOW, did this movie really deliver on its visuals. The scene where Owen is being chased by raptors on the bike was filmed in an amazing way. And that one scene where Claire was forced to hide from that big-ass dinosaur under the lake gave me anxiety. Overall, this movie may have had a nostalgic cast and amazing visuals, but it doesn't take away from the fact that this movie felt less Jurassic in every way possible. 7/10.

RANK & FILE MOVIE REVIEW: Jurassic World Dominion
boydedward-2500213 June 2022
Jurassic World Dominion currently sits at just a 38% on Rotten Tomatoes and it prompted me to do my first movie review. I wondered to myself why so often do critics get it wrong? I'm not alone in this thought because here are the stats from critic's vs audience. I see this so often and I had to ask myself why is this? I think the honest answer is that critics are there because they must be, and audiences are there because they want to be. As the movie starts and the Universal logo rolled into place, I was brought back to my thirteen-year-old self. Jurassic Park came out June 9th, 1993. Twenty-nine years ago. It honestly changed movies forever for me. I have seen every Jurassic Park movie, and Jurassic World movie in the theatre. I remember a group of us going from prom to see the midnight showing of the Lost World when it came out dressed in full tux and gowns. That is fan dedication! So, to get into the Jurassic World Dominion, it is everything it should be, but not everything it could be. The film is a little long at 2 hours and 26 minutes, but it does go by quick. Colin Trevorrow sits in the director's chair again as he did in the Jurassic World (2015). As an artist I am always curious as to who the films cinematographer is? In this case, it was John Schwartzman. The film is stunning. The visuals and dinosaur effects are awesome. I appreciated the return to a lot of the practical dinosaur effects. The plot has everything a good dinosaur plot should have and a little bit more. No spoilers, but this is a straight up dinosaur James Bond movie. Personally, I love James Bond, but that was a point of contention for the critics. DeWanda Wise was a scene stealer as the dubbed Han Solo of Jurassic Park. She calls out another character in the film named Denise who your led to believe was a girlfriend? I am not sure if she is the first LGBTQ+ character in the franchise, but regardless she's great. It is also great to see all the legacy cast return. Laura Dern, Sam Neil, and of course Jeff Goldblum. The cast does become a bit of a scooby gang, and never quite feel like anything bad is going to happen to them. Alright, on to the big bad. Giganotosaurus. Well, he's bad but unintentionally gets upstaged by the Therizinosaurus (had to look that up twice) a terrifying Freddy Kruger like dinosaur. There is scene where it stalks Bryce Dallas Howard's (Claire) into a lake, and it is truly the stuff nightmares are made of. We also finally get to see the return of the dilophosaurus. The film is at its best mid-way through when a chase scene filmed in Malta breaks out. It was a real seat clencher. So, to land this review home I am going to bring it back to it was everything it should be, but not everything it could be. As far as where it lays in the franchise, I would say it falls nicely into third place behind Jurassic Park, and Jurassic World.

Now, hear me out. I am a HUGE Jurassic Park-World fan, I have seen the movies dozen of times each, I absolutely enjoy them and it doesn't get boring to me. I actually really enjoyed this movie too, and there are some things to note:

  • it has so many reference scenes to all the movies, so many! It becomes a sort of game, thinking, remembering and trying to figure out if the scene is somewhat similar to any of all the other movies (I counted at least 1 scene per movie, but there could easily be more).


  • seeing the most important characters of ALL of the movies here was something else! A nice way to say goodbye to the saga, if you ask me.


  • it has a lot of action, as expected, and it kept me on the edge of my seat most of the time. I kept jumping, covering my face, and just being fully there, which goes to show how much of a fan I am (all the friends I went with have not seen all the other Jurassic World movies (just the first Jurassic Park ones) so there's a lot they didn't understand)


With this said, I have seen many amazing (8 or 9 star rated) movies from a technical standpoint, and this movie might just not qualify to be on that list. As a fan? LOVED it, but realistically people will argue it's the same old thing: same old storyline and no development of it, same plot twists as per usual.

So here's my final thought: I love it, I am already planning on going to watch it a second and maybe third time, because as a fan, I just want to say goodbye to my favourite characters and enjoy the end of an era.

After seeing the pitiful reviews and absolutely awful critic reviews, I doubted that this movie would be enjoyable in the least, but after seeing it, it was much more enjoyable, at least in my own opinion, than the reviews make it out to me. As someone who isn't completely obsessed with the Jurassic Park series, I was not paying too much attention for what it could have done after the expansion of opportunities, which it missed in Fallen Kingdom with the world of dinosaurs, but what the movie offered on its own. I think the plot line was fantastic, even if seemingly overused, it was done correctly. The direction at the beginning of the movie seemed confusing, but it made those connections more understandable by the end of the movie. The return of characters from JP1 was done quite fantastically, with all actors having the same feel and personality as in JP1. Jeff Goldblum was especially great in his return as Dr. Ian Malcolm, with his role in the plot making sense and with some great ad libs. The audio design was fantastic, with the surrounding environment being perfectly balanced, making you feel more interested and on your toes in scenes. John Williams did a fantastic job with the music, with new music making scenes more thrilling, as well as imputing the original theme correctly and in tone with the scenes. But the movie was not perfect on all fronts. The villain of Dr. Lewis Dodgson felt undeveloped and just cruel at times, even with the development in Fallen Kingdom. There are some areas that feel skipped over and other that feel overdone, such as the lack of comedy for most of the film, and too much comedy in certain parts. Some scenes were made too serious and others not serious enough. The film lacked balance at some points, but the movie did not disappoint as much as I feel the reviews might say. Its not perfect, but it is worth a rewatch or two once it releases on streaming services.

Great aesthetics and cinematography
RyanAmmon9 June 2022
I'm so glad that this was a well put together film. It was beautifully shot, decently paced, and had a good balance of story, character focus, and, of course, action. It felt like Jurassic Park meets Bourne Identity, with a twist of Indiana Jones and even a bit Star Warsy at times. Like a Star Wars level of world immersion, where they took us away and we experienced a new world where dinosaurs were now integrated into some parts of society. The scene in Malta was totally comparable to a Star Wars Cantina scene.

The aesthetic and cinematography of Dominion made me more nostalgic than seeing the original cast. The shots were a little more hard lit and gritty than what we're used to, versus the overly HDR hyperreal, super clean visuals we expect to see in most blockbuster movies. Dominion felt a lot more grounded and classically cinematic. Back and side lighting for the win.

I enjoyed the focus and interactions between the large cast of characters, both old, older and new. It didn't feel like anyone overly dominated the screen, with everyone sharing a place, a purpose and a voice before finally uniting for a fun and exciting climax. The dinosaurs also didn't overtake the story, allowing the human elements to breath, with their appearances serving as well timed spectacles that complimented the overall world and story. Visually this is the best we've seen, and I wasn't sure at times if they brought back the animatronics, or the CGI has improved a lot more for this film. I think it may have been a mix of both.

I really think that they went through the previous films in the series, saw what work and what didn't work, and put their efforts into not making the the same old mistakes. While simultaneously brainstorming a bucket list of new things they wanted to bring to life and create on screen. Like of course, if you have to compete with a baby Yoda it makes sense to create a baby Blue. Overall for me this was the strongest of the sequel trilogy, and a strong contender for the second best in the saga. I wouldn't be surprised if we hear another TV series announced some time soon based on this Jurassic World.

Putting everyone's favorite raptors on there like they have lots of screen time when they don't. Owen and Blue's bond was barely touched on. And there are so many holes in the plot that I got confused bc nothing really made any sense.

I guess I'll just start going through some of the things that didn't add up for me.. The pilot helping.. why? There was nothing remarkable about Kayla seeing Maisie during the trade off. No words spoken, not something similar happening to her or a love one, nothing. It made no sense that a pilot for hire would do anything for strangers, for free.

The locusts. I know the scientists stated that they were more hardy but that hardly constitutes that a swarm of locusts could survive AND FLY while burning, for the amount of time that they did. Their wings would've been the first thing to burn up but in the movie they fly around long enough to escape a building and fly around to set miles of forest ablaze. Ye...no.

While we're talking about burning locusts, when Malcolm threw the spear into the mouth of the Giganotosaurus and it... exploded, making him look like he could breathe fire. That's not how that works.. Just no.

T-Rex/Therizinosaurus vs Giganotosaurus. I think this made me the most upset. There was no explanation about the long clawed, seemingly blind dinosaur that pops up and seems intent on disemboweling everything. And the fact that it seemed to form a pact with the T-Rex makes no sense. There was no bond like with the T-Rex and Blue and the fight seemed pointless in general. And why wouldn't the Therizinosaurus not attack Rex after?

It's like they knew they had this super flimsy plot and decided to fill it full of JP nostalgia and lots of pointless action to keep us distracted. This wasn't a JP or JW movie, it was an action flick with dinosaurs thrown into it. So I mean, entertaining for sure but a very big flop for me.

Not as bad as all the big critics are claiming
pyronuke11 June 2022
As an avid action flick fan, I really enjoyed Dominion. But I don't understand why so many are dead set on this being the worst one of the franchise. (Come on guys, is it really worse than JP3 or Fallen Kingdom?) Most of the reviews from popular critics like to call out Dominion's length and how it "is a soulless imitation banking on nostalgia." However, of the six Jurassic Park movies, this is not the worst by a long shot.

While the length at 2 1/2 hours is a bit of a detriment, "soulless" is not the word I would use. Dominion pays off to many of the themes that have been set up by Jurassic World and Fallen Kingdom. None of the characters are obnoxious to the point of unlikable. The cinematography and especially the sound design are very well done. The plot, though a bit chaotic, can still be followed easily enough.

However, the film still has its flaws. Some of the side plots don't get enough attention, and the villain is a little sub-par. The second half follows the humans a lot more than the dinosaurs, and that could be a turn off for fans of the franchise. The aforementioned length does make it difficult for those with short attention spans to sit through. By the 2/3rd point I was staring to notice it hadn't wrapped up yet, but the pacing was well done and at no point was I ever bored.

So why are so many big-name critics so willing to throw Dominion under the bus? I have a theory. After so many sequels that failed to capture the magic of the original, encluding Dominion, these critics take their anger of a franchise as a whole and apply it to the latest film. The problem is that the original was truly one-of-a-kind, and very few movies can hold a candle to it. It would take nothing short of a miracle to surpass the original Jurassic Park.

The other thing I have noticed it that there has been an increasing disconnect between critics and audiences. Many review websites, YouTube channels, and social media outlets like posting negative reviews because that's what gets the clicks. I get it; it's fun to write and to read slander about something you disagree with, but if you only focus on the bad then that is all you'll ever find.

Overall, by no means perfect, it is a decent and effective conclusion to the Jurassic World trilogy.

Novelty, action adventure, and monster horror are what made the original Jurassic Park amazing. Jurassic World: Dominion checks the action adventure box. At times, the monster horror box. But, it always falls short on novelty.

You can't be surprised by this. After all this is the 6th installment of the series. Novelty left the building awhile ago.

The Jurassic series chief conflict has always been man's desire to control nature, and despite the warnings of Jeff Goldblum we attempt it time and time again. Jurassic World: Dominion attempts to wrap up this conflict, and it does, albeit it in an unsatisfying way.

There are three groups we follow through out the film. Each pursuing their own goals until they eventually converge. One of these story lines is good. The other two seem like filler with even one of them not having any real tangible effect.

Jurassic World: Dominion try's. It try's really freaking hard. And when it hits it hits right. Those moments are just so few and far between. Honestly, if you take away the star power of Chris Pratt, Jeff Goldblum, and the call back cast from the original. It comes off like an early 2000's sequel that should have gone straight to dvd.

I don't think it's a terrible movie. But I do think it falls short of even being a good film. If you like the new Jurassic World movies you'll like this as well. If not, we'll at least the dinosaurs look pretty.

Oh, and there is an evil version of Tim Cook.

Far better than Fallen Kingdom and a worthy conclusion
ryanthomasmitchell10 June 2022
I don't know what people were expecting with this movie and why many seem to be up in arms about it. I am a big fan of the first film and saw it in theaters as a child upon its release. For many, including myself, the magic of that first movie is never going to be topped and it's impossible to think it could be.

That said, the second film has always been dull to me (and Jeff Goldblum seemed to be playing a different character than Ian Malcolm altogether). The third has solid moments but some silly ones as well. Jurassic World seemed to rejuvenate the franchise and was a good movie overall, but nothing mind-blowing in my opinion.

Then we have Fallen Kingdom, which I believe is easily the worst in the series. Strange plot, terrible pacing, weird directorial choices left and right. The main characters and their motivations seemed completely different than what you would have expected from their portrayal in Jurassic World.

That movie also ended with the concept of a world filled with dinosaurs - a point which people seem to be rolling their eyes about, now that Dominion has to address it.

This is unfair. Dominion is a movie that must take the plot threads that are limply presented in Fallen Kingdom and then spin a sequel out of them. On top of that, it must weave in the cast of the beloved first film and make a satisfying conclusion out of both stories.

And guess what? I think it accomplishes this, and much better than I expected it would. The movie is exciting, well-paced, well-acted, and has far fewer eyeroll moments than the critics would have you believe.

At this point, I think you're either along for the ride or you aren't. If you're only casually aware of Jurassic Park and you go into this movie somewhat blind, it would probably seem like a mess of convoluted plot points. But if you're coming off of Fallen Kingdom, this feels like a breath of fresh air and a fun ride.

I would honestly rank this movie as the second best Jurassic Park movie, behind the original. And Ian Malcolm's portrayal in this film is perfect, unlike what we got in Lost World. It's a joy to see.

Fun, but flawed thrills
buddycsb12 June 2022
Ladies and gentlemen, it's here.

The finale of the entire Jurassic series has finally arrived in theatres.

Jurassic World: Dominion is a fun, thrilling action adventure story with dinosaurs. This film is filled with the typical dinosaur action sequences, a couple of which can feel indicative of Jason Bourne and Indiana Jones action scenes.

Bringing back the original three was a stroke of genius and I appreciated how they fit them into the plot without them feeling shoehorned in.

Where this movie fails for me was the flimsy plot.

If you start to think, there are lots of coincidences and inconsistencies that push the plot forward.

This film is not smartly written like some blockbusters today. It is nowhere near as smart as the original film.

This film promised a story about dinosaurs in the real world, but instead it uses that as a catalyst for a story that has nothing to do with them being out in the real world. I feel as though this story could have been told if the cliffhanger from Fallen Kingdom never even happened.

Beyond that, if this film was trying to produce a satisfying conclusion to each trilogy's story it horrendously failed. If it was simply trying to get me to smile really quick at seeing the original cast again, it succeeded spectacularly.

In conclusion, this film is a one-watch scenario for me. It delivers the thrills of dinosaur action sequences and the joy of seeing my childhood heroes back on the screen. However, it did not fully deliver on the promise of a plot based around dinosaurs in the wild and it did not deliver the proper conclusion for the characters we've been following.

The cast ranking Laura Dern Sam Neill Jeff Goldblum DeWanda Wise Campbell Scott Bryce Dallas Howard Chris Pratt Isabella Sermon

Chris Pratt is my favorite actor, but I was so disappointed with how little the script gave him to work with.

The Dominion of the Jurassic Franchise Is Slightly Disappointing.
epiclyyep11 June 2022
There are no spoilers in this review.

Jurassic World Dominion take its setting four years after the events of Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom. Dominion is the grand, spectacular, finale of the Jurassic World trilogy, and the Jurassic Park franchise as a whole. At least... that's what it was supposed to be.

First off, I did not hate the film. It's not a film that I would never watch again in my life. The reason for my slight disappointment, I state below.

CONS: There are absolutely no character arcs in this film, besides one character, which I won't spoil here. Maisie Lockwood may also have a small arc from her behavior... but that's it. Second off, I thought that this film was too focused on demonstrating action sequences. Rather than exploring the scientific narrative behind the story, it chose to have a jam-packed film filled with action. Sometimes, that's not bad. Colin Trevorrow, the Director of this and the first Jurassic World film, had to please both the action-seeking audience AND the story-seeking audience. I am part of the latter half. So, I understand the action sequences, but it gets overwhelming at points. Focus less on biking/escaping/running/fighting scenes, and concoct a better story! That leads me to my next point. The story feels very hollow and rushed. For a 2-and-a-half-hour-long film, you'd expect the ending to have a magnitude that's different from the ending of the previous film. However, nothing changes. Dinosaurs still roam across the world. Maybe there are two character arcs, but other than that, there's no change from the ending of JW:FK.

PROS: There is a well-written plot twist midway through the film that I enjoyed watching. It gives some more expansion to the JW "lore". Some moments in JWD gave me some seriously intense moments, where I felt like I was going to sweat. Mr. Trevorrow did fantastic on that sweet, sweet, tension. The addition of a few new characters is nice to see. Now, we have the classic characters, the classic JW characters, and the newer characters. Jeff Goldblum is phenomenal in this film and had some humor that made me laugh out loud. A lot of people disliked the locust side story, but personally, I saw it as a way to connect the two stories into one. It was a way to bring the classic characters into the story. I liked that there were also multiple plot lines to follow. Some say that this should have been split into two parts, but these stories happen at the same time, so it would be confusing to have two parts.

Overall, JWD had some major flaws in its production, but I respect and admire the crew's work and struggle through COVID-19. They did the best they could. This movie may not be the best installment, but it's certainly better that JPIII.

Also, this movie doesn't deserve the rotten tomatoes score it has. It's really not THAT bad...

A movie WITH dinosaurs, not ABOUT dinosaurs

Warning: Spoilers
0 out of 1 found this helpful. Was this review helpful? Sign in to vote.
Permalink
'Jurassic World' breathed new life into the 'Jurassic Park' franchise. And much like the original, is far and away the best of the trilogy.

I had high hopes for 'Dominion'. After the dinosaurs escaped at the end of 'Fallen Kingdom', and the short that was released a couple years ago that show dinosaurs invading a camp site, I hoped we would get to see how humans and dinosaurs co-exist in the world. But aside from some news clippings at the beginning and end, we really don't see much of it. There is a storyline about there being a black market for dinosaurs, but the main story revolved around....mutant locusts?

Of course an evil corporation is behind it, intent to control the world's food supply.

Dinosaurs kind of take a back seat, and feel like they make more cameos than anything. In fact, I wouldn't be entirely surprised if I found out that there were fewer dinosaurs with less screen time than any other movie. As many as they packed into 'Fallen Kingdom', especially when the volcano exploded, that's how few are in this film. That being said, a dinosaur did provide a pretty good jump scare.

There also didn't real feel like that big, bad "villain" dinosaur, like the T-Rex in the original, the Spinosaurus in 3, the Indominus Rex in World, or the IndoRaptor in 'Fallen Kingdom'. They introduce the Giganotosaurus, but it felt more like a throw away than anything.

Don't get me wrong, this isn't necessarily a bad movie, but it just feels like more of a distant relative of 'World'. There was a bit of nostalgia having the original cast back, and the Barbasol can even has a cameo.

If it didn't carry the Jurassic World name, this may have been a more favorable review. But it's really not a great Jurassic Park movie.

Starting info: Now i can definitely see why this movie is getting bad reviews, and low ratings, From the first half an hour, the movie is unbelievably and unbearably BORING, it all face paced, yet so slow.. Once it starts to take off, it becomes super overwhelming and hard to process because of how scrambled and fast paced all the action sequences are.. (1/6)

Plot: The plot isn't as bad as everyone makes it out to seem, but it is definitely NOT executed well, it is fairly predictable, and cliche. Which makes the film NOT feel like a jurassic park/movie in anyway possible. (2/6)

Characters and acting: I absolutely loved the acting from Chris pratt, dewanda wise & Sam Neil!, although the downsides were that the original trio didnt seem recognizable at ALL! Ellie sattler just seemed like an over dramatic b*tch, Alan grant just looked like an old sad fart who's still has a love interest after like 40 years, and i feel like ian malcom was just there just because it wouldnt make sense to have the other 2 original characters and not him there so they just through him in there for the sake of it , even though in the movie it feels like he was only shown for like 6 minutes.

And the villains were super cliche, corny and stupid!, they just made the movie so much worse than it needed to be! (3/6)

Action: The action in this movie is top notch, but once again, theres too much happening, you either get confused, or you get overwhelmed. The dinosaur fights were short as all hell and underwhelming, ESPECIALLY the last fight scene. But the suspence is awesome! Some scenes send chills down your spine, but could have been done alot better. (4/6)

Ending: After a very short and underwhelming battle between dinosaurs, the main characters find themselves back in an airport, safe and sound which doesnt feel satisfying one bit.. it feels like a half of the movie was unfinished, or like you won a competition but know you cheated. It just doesnt feel genuine and completed. (5/6)

All in all, if you are someone who wants to see alot of dinosaur action, want to relax on a weekend and go watch a movie with your friends, Go check it out. Just dont go expecting some movie thats going to have a reward for 10/10 drama, acting and storyline. Just go enjoy it! (6/6)

I enjoyed the idea of the first one. Jurassic World was a great concept and panned out very well. Dominion took the key idea of Jurassic World and put it in a different situation with the main characters, not the best idea, but it was still a decent film.

This third movie came out of nowhere. The dialogue was unnatural, lacking in personality and depth. Making what was three dimensional characters in to one dimensional. Any added characters were simple and lacking in depth. One of the most frustrating portions was bringing back the classic three characters and completely ruining their them. All actors could not save the script with their skill, nor could the director with his. The biggest flaw was in its very foundation, the script. The plot itself is a story of agricultural control and demise... with dinosaurs and a clone.

The VFX, the acting, the direction, and the action were there. That is why I give it a 5 star rating. It still had key components that would make a film good. But a film can only be as good as it's base foundation, no matter how much money and fame you throw at it. It is truly unfortunate that this film felt like a cash grab. I hope that if they want to proceed in making any more films in the Jurassic Park franchise, they focus on what the original was.

There was no other way to finish it, so I get it.
fenonfive13 June 2022
To me, this ending made the most sense given all that we've seen and done over the course of the previous 5 movies. We've seen the big dinosaur fights. We've seen the genetically modifed dinosaurs. We've seen the main characters in dino danger many many many times. We even got to see the park come together the way we knew it could be. I understand it's what we love, but with this being the very last movie, I know they had to be careful about tying up loose ends while also keeping us entertained.

To me, this type of ending made the most sense. The nostalgia factor was high and I thought that was a really good move to include the OG cast. We have our closure and we feel good about all they've accomplished. The park has been done, the dinos being released into the "real world" has been done - what was left other than to close up the genetics storyline and make sure we understood that the dinos weren't going anywhere? You can't put it all back in the box, so there was nowhere else left to go.

I guess I just don't see what people were expecting. There was plenty of action given. We've had all the wow moments we wanted, and I felt this movie did a decent job at giving us Dino scares mixed with real story. Was the "magic" there? Not exactlyyyy- and while I appreciate the nods to previous movies with the dino fights, it did feel a bit lazy. But it's the end so I didn't go in expecting some big twist and surprise. We knew what was coming and needed it to be wrapped up tightly, give a nod to all that we've seen and done and that came before us, and say goodbye. I felt this did exactly that and nothing more, so I appreciate it.
